    1: # A Functional Architecture for Distributed Governance: Mechanism Design, Adversarial Stress-Testing, and a Symmetric Computational Test of Selective Institutional Distribution
    2: 
    3: **Working paper — v1.13 (July 2026; latest deposited version: v1.12, DOI 10.5281/zenodo.21252911). This version retires the earlier compound value-per-budget multiplier as a calibrated effect — a pre-registered symmetric selection-only stress test returned NO-GO (see §6 and the claim & estimand contract) — and rests on the architecture and the qualitative mechanism. Revised through successive adversarial and author review cycles, documented in the repository's roadmap. It consolidates the companion computational program (Offermann 2026b): the deterrence-complementarity rule, the semi-open transition path, the budget-release rule, and machine verification with the human second instance; and the companion's two-layer separation of the macro categorization from the allocation profiles, under which the distributed arm is robust to a bad central categorization while the central arm is fragile to it.**
    4: 
    5: *© 2026 Mauricio Offermann. Licensed CC BY 4.0 — see LICENSE.md at the repository root. Please cite as indicated in CITATION.cff. DOI (concept, always resolves to the latest version): 10.5281/zenodo.21193846.*
    6: 
    7: ## Abstract
    8: 
    9: Public resources are allocated and controlled by institutions that fuse three functions — who selects projects, who executes them, and who judges whether they delivered. That fusion is where waste, capture, and unaccountable failure concentrate. This paper asks whether a bounded share of that machinery can separate those functions — and the information that drives them — while preserving legal authorization and public auditability.
   10: 
   11: We present **Core v0**, a fully specified, object-level architecture. Within legally authorized planning scopes, citizens direct a non-withdrawable share of an existing public budget to projects that must declare value claims, affected parties, milestones, and evidence contracts up front. Proposing, execution, evidence production, fiscalization, and custody are separated; funds move in tranches against reviewed milestone evidence, with retention and guarantees; executors neither choose nor pay their inspectors; and every consequential state transition is public.
   12: 
   13: Its animating idea is a **credit-versus-coverage** mechanism: when central ranking rewards claimable political credit, it can systematically underweight the diffuse, low-visibility benefits that a coverage-based distributed process still surfaces, albeit under voice bias. We held this idea to a deliberately hostile test — a pre-registered, symmetric simulation that stripped out the favorable asymmetries an earlier version had relied on, plus a public adversarial review of 43 attacks across five rounds, each integrated into the design or recorded as a bounded limitation. The distributed advantage was positive in all 18 pre-specified cells but small (pooled median Δ = 0.025 of a full-information greedy benchmark, below our pre-set 0.05 threshold); we therefore retire the large multiplier an earlier version reported and state the modest, conditional result plainly. Elementary propositions give sufficient conditions for incentive-compatible disbursement and collusion-proof fiscalization under independence and corroboration assumptions.
   14: 
   15: This is an architecture-and-mechanism contribution, not an impact evaluation: no pilot has run; the simulation's units are uncalibrated and partial-equilibrium and do not identify delivery effects; and claims are scoped to infrastructure-like public investment. What it offers is a concrete, criticizable, pilotable institutional design — and a disciplined account of exactly what its evidence does and does not yet support.
   16: 
   17: ## 1. Introduction
   18: 
   19: Modern states concentrate three things that need not sit together: the
   20: authority to decide what public money is spent on, the capacity to execute
   21: that spending, and the power to certify that it achieved anything. When all
   22: three live inside one hierarchy, accountability comes down to it auditing
   23: itself (Bovens 2007). The consequences are predictable and documented across
   24: political economy — discretionary allocation, self-reported compliance,
   25: capture by concentrated interests, and citizen distrust — from regulatory
   26: capture (Stigler 1971; Laffont and Tirole 1991) to audit turned ritual (Power
   27: 1997) to the distributional coalitions that entrench themselves in stable
   28: political systems (Olson 1982).
   29: 
   30: These failures are not abstract: they are why the value never reaches the
   31: people it was raised for. For the public money that funds concrete projects —
   32: infrastructure, works, local programs — what ultimately matters is not how much
   33: is appropriated but how much effective value reaches people per unit spent: a
   34: project that is never built, or built badly, helps no one, however
   35: well-intentioned the allocation (Okun's (1975) leaky bucket carried water that
   36: never arrived). This is a bounded criterion for project-type public investment,
   37: not a theory of the whole budget or of why states tax: redistribution and equity
   38: are distinct purposes of public finance that this paper does not evaluate (§8).
   39: 
   40: The standard debate responds with quantity: shrink the state or grow it. Both
   41: positions treat it as a single object. This paper argues the tractable
   42: question is architectural, not one of size: *which layers of state activity
   43: still require central monopoly, and which can now be distributed — with better
   44: accountability than the status quo — now that digital coordination has
   45: collapsed the transaction costs that once justified hierarchy?* (Coase 1937;
   46: Hayek 1945; Williamson 1985). It is a question with a lineage — where
   47: decisions should sit when knowledge is dispersed — from the economic
   48: calculation debate (Mises 1920) to Hayek's dispersed knowledge and its
   49: institutional treatment in Sowell (1980): decisions should live where the
   50: knowledge is, disciplined by feedback rather than top-down command. Rights
   51: guarantees, legitimate force, macro-fiscal stability, and enforceable
   52: adjudication plausibly remain central; information processing, project-level
   53: resource allocation, service execution, evidence production, and auditing
   54: plausibly do not.
   55: 
   56: We make the argument as a concrete design, not a manifesto. Core v0 is a
   57: complete reference architecture for distributing one bounded layer — the
   58: allocation, execution, and verification of a legally mandated share of an
   59: existing public budget — developed to the level of named objects, state
   60: machines, and decision rules (a corpus of more than one hundred architecture
   61: documents, fifty-nine designed hypotheses, and forty-three adversarial reviews, all
   62: public). Citizens receive periodic, non-withdrawable allocation capacity in a
   63: civic wallet; projects pass through a parallel-closure lifecycle in which
   64: funding, independent fiscalization, evidence commitments, and beneficiary
   65: confirmation must all close before execution; the executor never selects or
   66: pays its own auditors — which removes the agency cost of self-monitored
   67: compliance (Jensen and Meckling 1976); money moves only on reviewed
   68: milestones, with retention and externally materialized guarantees; and every
   69: consequential state transition is recorded in a citizen-legible,
   70: expert-auditable trail.
   71: 
   72: The *executor* —whoever carries out the project, be it a public work, a
   73: personal-care service, or an educational program— can be a public agency, a
   74: municipality, a foundation, a cooperative, or a firm, as the implementing
   75: authority's rules define, under one condition: non-monopolistic, honest
   76: competition, with bankruptcies and consequences for whoever fails to deliver.
   77: And the share each citizen directs is set by a public, versioned formula the
   78: authority chooses; its simple option is *equal for all eligible citizens*,
   79: under which no one buys more influence with more money.
   80: 
   81: A concrete example. Suppose a municipality funds care programs for vulnerable
   82: elderly people. Today, between the peso allocated and the help that actually
   83: arrives lies a gap where value is lost. Under this architecture, each resident
   84: can direct part of their taxes to the program they prefer; the foundation,
   85: cooperative, or service that carries it out is paid in tranches, and only once
   86: a verifier it did not choose confirms the help arrived; and every step is
   87: public and auditable.
   88: 
   89: What makes a design exercise count as research is the rigor it is put through,
   90: under one transversal discipline: every claim is evaluated against how the
   91: current institution solves the same problem, not against an ideal — blocking the nirvana fallacy —comparing the real institution against an unattainable ideal rather than the available alternative— in both directions (Section 2). Our contributions are:
   92: 
   93: 1. **Distributing the allocation layer.** The core design contribution:
   94:    applying the functional-distribution principle to resource allocation —
   95:    citizens direct their share directly, delegate it, or govern it with
   96:    personal rules — instantiated as a complete reference architecture (Core
   97:    v0).
   98: 
   99: 2. **Formalization of the incentive mechanisms** (Section 5). We model
  100:    milestone-gated disbursement as a principal-agent game and derive its
  101:    incentive-compatibility condition; we model bribery of protocol-assigned
  102:    fiscalizers and derive a collusion-proofness condition under
  103:    k-corroboration; and we prove two design-relevant comparative statics: weak
  104:    verification must be compensated with financial terms, and guarantees are
  105:    counterproductive when detection quality falls below the cost of capital.
  106:    Milestones, retention, guarantees, and reputational memory form the
  107:    design's deterrence stack.
  108: 
  109: 3. **Computational evidence** (Section 6). A dependency-free, seeded
  110:    agent-based simulation of 10,000 citizens tests the architecture's
  111:    behavioral assumptions under rational ignorance, limited discovery
  112:    attention, and social-proof cascades. The results discipline the design:
  113:    they support some claims, sharpen others, quantify the leverage
  114:    concentrated in the scope-construction layer, measure a viable open
  115:    construction of it, and carry the comparison end to end: from allocation to
  116:    delivered social value per unit of budget — one relevant criterion for this
  117:    bounded slice of public spending (alongside distributional and rights
  118:    constraints the model does not represent). In the model, verified delivery and social prioritization
  119:    interact rather than merely add; the earlier agent-based apparatus produced a
  120:    compound of 2.22× a status-quo baseline parameterized from published
  121:    audit-institution findings (1.4–1.6× at municipal pilot scale). We **retire
  122:    that compound as a calibrated effect**: a pre-registered, symmetric,
  123:    selection-only stress test shrinks the distributed-minus-central selection
  124:    advantage to a pre-registered pooled median Δ = 0.025 of a full-information
  125:    benchmark, below its pre-set 0.05 research-program rebuild gate (NO-GO). The
  126:    load-bearing contribution is the architecture and the
  127:    mechanism *direction*, not the multiplier.
  128: 
  129: 4. **Adversarial review as method** (Section 7). The architecture was attacked
  130:    systematically: forty-three attack briefs grounded in the political-science,
  131:    economics, and law literatures, each answered by a paired defense and
  132:    resolved under an explicit integrate-or-bound rule, with resolutions
  133:    propagated through the corpus (all except the manuscript-review round's
  134:    D037–D040, whose corpus propagation is tracked) and the full review
  135:    record public by construction. The loop is a structured self-critique, not external
  136:    validation, and we say so; we propose it, and its terminating rule—pending independent external validation—as a preliminary methodological proposal for institutional design research.
  137: 
  138: A companion study measures three effects that extend this architecture:
  139: ablation of the deterrence stack (its terms are individually redundant but
  140: jointly indispensable), the feasibility of AI-based fiscalization, and the
  141: effect of separating macro planning from allocation (robustness to poor
  142: central planning — an earlier-apparatus contrast, subject to the same
  143: magnitude caveat as the compound above, not a calibrated effect).
  144: 
  145: Section 8 states limitations with the same care as results, because under our
  146: method they are results: each is a named, bounded residual risk.
  147: 
  148: ## 2. The functional distribution principle
  149: 
  150: We analyze the state as a stack of functional layers rather than a single
  151: institution: (a) rights guarantees and legitimate force; (b) binding
  152: adjudication; (c) rule-making; (d) macro-fiscal management; (e) macro planning
  153: and agenda framing; (f) project prioritization and resource allocation to
  154: concrete projects; (g) execution and service delivery; (h) evidence production
  155: about delivery; and (i) evaluation and accountability. The distribution
  156: principle is:
  157: 
  158: > A layer is a candidate for distribution when three conditions hold:
  159: > its failures under monopoly are information and incentive failures rather
  160: > than coordination-of-force failures; distributed provision can be made
  161: > *more* observable than monopoly provision; and the layer can be bounded so
  162: > that its failure does not cascade into the non-distributable layers.
  163: 
  164: Layers (a), (b), and (d) fail the first or third condition and remain central
  165: in our design. Layers (f) through (i) pass all three, and Core v0 distributes them as a block, and must: distributing allocation without verification reproduces the delivery gap of participatory budgeting (PB), and distributing verification without allocation reproduces the audit society.
  166: 
  167: Layer (e), planning, is the deliberately unresolved case: Core v0 requires
  168: planning scopes to be public, versioned, and mandate-bearing, but does not
  169: distribute their construction — which is why the architecture's promise is
  170: stated with its qualifier built in: what it distributes is allocation
  171: *within mandate-bound, visible, versioned, and contestable planning
  172: scopes*, never allocation over an unframed agenda. Section 6 shows the
  173: qualifier is not a detail: it is the binding constraint of the whole
  174: design, and Section 8 elevates its removal to the research program's next
  175: object.
  176: 
  177: Two methodological rules govern everything that follows. The **comparative
  178: critique rule** (P001): every objection is evaluated against the current
  179: institutional baseline, not an ideal — a difficulty shared by both systems
  180: is a general problem of governance, not a refutation of the proposal. The
  181: **integrate-or-bound rule** (P007): once the core architecture is complete,
  182: a founded objection produces a new mechanism only if the failure mode would
  183: defeat a core claim and cannot be controlled through existing objects;
  184: otherwise it produces an explicit boundary, a visible residual risk, and a
  185: limitation statement. The first rule disciplines critics; the second
  186: disciplines the designers — a bias toward few, simple, general rules over
  187: proliferating specific machinery in the spirit of Epstein (1995).
  188: 
  189: ## 3. Related work
  190: 
  191: **Polycentric governance.** Ostrom's demonstration that common-pool
  192: resources can be governed by nested, self-organized regimes without central
  193: monopoly (Ostrom 1990) is the closest intellectual ancestor: her design
  194: principles — bounded scope, monitoring by accountable monitors, graduated
  195: sanctions, cheap conflict resolution — reappear here as software-enforced
  196: objects. The difference is scope and instrument: we target budgeted state
  197: functions rather than natural-resource commons, and encode the regime in a
  198: platform whose rule changes are themselves versioned, auditable objects.
  199: 
  200: **Participatory budgeting.** Porto Alegre-style PB delegates a share of a
  201: municipal budget to citizen assemblies (Wampler 2007; Baiocchi and Ganuza
  202: 2017). Empirically, PB improves some fiscal outcomes but suffers from
  203: engagement decay, capture by organized minorities, and weak links between
  204: allocation and verified delivery (Peixoto and Fox 2016). Core v0 differs on
  205: exactly those margins: allocation is continuous and individual rather than
  206: assembly-based; delivery is bound to allocation through evidential contracts
  207: and conditional disbursement; and the architecture treats low participation
  208: as a design input (Section 6) rather than a failure to be exhorted away —
  209: collective action does not sustain itself at scale (Olson 1965).
  210: The civic wallet itself generalizes the voucher mechanism (Friedman 1962) —
  211: citizen-directed public money — from choosing among service providers to
  212: allocating among verifiable projects, adding the verification lifecycle
  213: that vouchers never carried.
  214: 
  215: **Fiscal federalism and epistemic democracy.** The formal ancestors of the
  216: functional distribution principle are the decentralization literature —
  217: Oates's (1972) theorem on when decentralized provision dominates, Tiebout
  218: (1956) on preference revelation through jurisdiction choice, and Besley
  219: and Coate (2003) on centralized versus decentralized provision under
  220: political economy — with one deliberate difference: our layers are
  221: functional rather than territorial, so what is distributed is a stage of
  222: the spending process (allocation, execution, verification) rather than a
  223: level of government. On the epistemic side, the aggregation results of
  224: Section 6 belong to the lineage of Condorcet's (1785) jury theorem and its
  225: modern failure conditions (Austen-Smith and Banks 1996) — a debt we make
  226: explicit, because the theorem's failure regime (correlated, strategic, or
  227: biased signals) is exactly what the seventh experiment stress-tests — and
  228: the design conversation with Landemore's (2020) open democracy and Fung
  229: and Wright's (2003) empowered participatory governance is direct: those
  230: programs distribute deliberation and empowerment; this one distributes
  231: allocation, execution, and verification with a mechanism-design and
  232: audit-trail core they do not attempt.
  233: 
  234: **Liquid democracy.** Transitive or scoped delegation promises flexibility
  235: between direct and representative participation, at the cost of concentration
  236: (Blum and Zuber 2016; Kahng, Mackenzie and Procaccia 2018). Core v0 adopts
  237: scoped, revocable, non-compensated delegation with mandatory concentration
  238: visibility, and — following Michels' (1911) warning rather than dismissing
  239: it — treats delegate concentration as a monitored risk with stress
  240: thresholds, not a solved problem.
  241: 
  242: **Digital and blockchain governance.** The DAO literature demonstrated both
  243: the feasibility of rule-encoded collective resource allocation and its
  244: characteristic failure: plutocratic token voting and governance capture (De
  245: Filippi and Wright 2018). Core v0 is deliberately not a blockchain design —
  246: identity is verified rather than pseudonymous, and the sovereign state
  247: remains the source of funds and law — but it imports the lesson that
  248: meta-governance is the highest-leverage attack surface (Section 8).
  249: 
  250: **Mechanism design and audit.** Our formal models are elementary
  251: applications of moral hazard under imperfect observation (Holmström 1979)
  252: and collusion in supervision hierarchies (Laffont and Tirole 1991), with
  253: Goodhart's law (Goodhart 1975; Campbell 1976) as the standing warning
  254: against metric gaming. The closest existing mechanism design for citizen
  255: allocation of public funds is quadratic (or 'plural') funding (Buterin, Hitzig
  256: and Weyl 2019), which prices concentration through matching-fund curvature;
  257: Core v0's funding-target closure rule pursues the same anti-concentration
  258: goal by truncation rather than pricing, and our simulation results
  259: (Section 6, Finding 1) delimit what truncation can and cannot achieve. On
  260: the audit side, Olken's (2007) field experiment on Indonesian road projects
  261: is the canonical empirical anchor for the detection probabilities our
  262: Propositions 1–2 take as parameters — and its finding that top-down audit
  263: outperformed grassroots monitoring for procurement fraud is a caution this
  264: architecture absorbs by making professional fiscalization, not crowd
  265: observation, the release-gating layer. The Brazilian audit-lottery
  266: literature (Ferraz and Finan 2008) supplies the complementary mechanism
  267: evidence — disclosure of audit findings changes political outcomes, and
  268: audit exposure reduces subsequent corruption — and its underlying CGU data
  269: enter the seventh experiment's audit-parameterized baseline directly. The contribution here is not
  270: technical depth but specificity: the models' parameters map one-to-one
  271: onto named architectural objects, so every proposition is an implementable
  272: dial.
  273: 
  274: **What is new.** We have not run the systematic prior-art review that would
  275: establish field-level priority (our literature map is preliminary), so we claim an
  276: **integrative, object-level synthesis** rather than novelty against all adjacent
  277: work. With that qualification, we are not aware of prior work combining:
  278: 
  279: - **(i)** a functional decomposition of state activity into distributable and
  280:   non-distributable layers;
  281: 
  282: - **(ii)** a complete object-level architecture for the allocation layer;
  283: 
  284: - **(iii)** formal incentive analysis of that architecture's specific
  285:   mechanisms;
  286: 
  287: - **(iv)** behavioral simulation of its citizen-facing assumptions —including
  288:   what we believe is an early symmetric-knowledge comparison, in simulation, of
  289:   open construction of allocation priorities from aggregated citizen signals
  290:   against bandwidth-constrained central construction (a later pre-registered
  291:   symmetric test finds the distributed advantage consistent but small; see Section 6)—;
  292: 
  293: - **(v)** a documented adversarial-review method with an explicit stopping
  294:   rule.
  295: 
  296: And two further contributions concern measurement and method:
  297: 
  298: - **(vi)** an end-to-end institutional comparison, within a bounded
  299:   public-investment slice, on delivered social value per unit of budget,
  300:   decomposing selection from delivery on matched portfolios (the two layers
  301:   interact within the exploratory apparatus). Separately, a later
  302:   pre-registered symmetric gate — a **selection-only** test with delivery held
  303:   at parity — finds the *selection* advantage positive but small (Section 6);
  304:   it does not test the delivery interaction. This work also introduces the
  305:   visibility gap (officially reported minus real delivery) as a
  306:   measurable accountability deficit of the status quo;
  307: 
  308: - **(vii)** that comparison against an audit-parameterized baseline built
  309:   from the published findings of supreme audit institutions across
  310:   nine jurisdictions and the European Union (a documented-practice-informed
  311:   scenario whose primary-source verification is still being completed), under a pre-registered
  312:   headline-withdrawal condition.
  313: 
  314: Participatory-budgeting evaluations measure participation and allocation;
  315: audit studies measure leakage after the fact; we know of none that measures,
  316: within one framework, how much delivered value an allocation institution
  317: produces from the same resources.
  318: 
  319: ## 4. The Core v0 architecture
  320: 
  321: We summarize the reference architecture at the level needed for the analysis;
  322: the full object model, state machines, and citizen-interface layers are
  323: specified in the public corpus.
  324: 
  325: **Funding.** An implementing authority migrates a mandated share of an
  326: existing budget into individual civic wallets: periodic, non-withdrawable,
  327: public-purpose allocation capacity, equal per citizen by default. Every active
  328: planning scope carries an *Allocation Mandate* record naming the statute or
  329: instrument that authorized the migration, its legal rank, the organ to which
  330: allocations are imputed, and the allocation formula. The platform records that
  331: external authorization; it does not manufacture it. Binding-mode operation is
  332: gated on an enabling norm of sufficient rank being recorded; otherwise, the
  333: disclosed lawful default is consultative or tutored operation. The allocation act is designed to replicate two guarantees of the vote: secrecy of the preference and coercion-resistance (receipt-freeness). To the extent an enabling norm recognizes it, it can be shielded with protections equivalent to the vote's; until then, these are technical platform guarantees, not a legal status. Individual allocations are pseudonymous at the public layer
  334: and reconcile cryptographically against public per-scope totals — every peso
  335: traceable as money, no citizen traceable as an allocator, and no receipt or
  336: exportable proof of any individual allocation exists, even voluntarily, so
  337: that a patron who demands proof can never get one (the secret ballot's own
  338: defense, applied to the wallet). A *Fiscal Commitment Profile* per scope makes
  339: the migrated percentage, indexation, and delivery latency public and
  340: versioned, so fiscal strangulation by the incumbent treasury is measurable and
  341: attributable rather than silent. Essential services with continuity
  342: obligations are protected by non-assignable floors outside citizen-by-citizen
  343: popularity.
  344: 
  345: **Projects and roles.** Financeable projects declare a value thesis with
  346: verifiable claims, affected parties, risks and anti-values, a phase and
  347: milestone plan, and an *evidential contract*: what must be proven, by what
  348: class of qualified producer, with what method, for which formal effect. Six
  349: roles are structurally separated — proposer, modeler/designer, executor,
  350: fiscalizer, evidence producer, custodian — with related-party relationships
  351: declared on a severity-classified graph. The load-bearing rule is that the
  352: executor never chooses or pays its own fiscalizers or evidence producers:
  353: control work is financed from a separated control budget and assigned by
  354: protocol.
  355: 
  356: **Parallel closure and conditional disbursement.** A published project
  357: gathers funding commitments, fiscalizer assignments, evidence commitments,
  358: and beneficiary confirmations concurrently; execution becomes possible only
  359: when all conditions required by its proportional *threshold policy* close.
  360: Committed funds are custodied, not transferred: release happens per
  361: milestone, against reviewed fulfillment evidence, with retention, blocker
  362: checks, and guarantees materialized by external custodians before any
  363: release. A *Duty-of-Care Anchor* names, before disbursement, the solvent legal person civilly answerable to third parties for damages arising from execution, in particular damage to physical integrity.
  364: 
  365: **Attention infrastructure.** Citizens act through a layered interface:
  366: discovery with user-controlled, reason-visible ordering; compact project
  367: cards; and progressively deeper audit surfaces down to the full trail.
  368: Non-attending citizens are served by configurable automatic allocation
  369: profiles — or a sensible default profile when none is set — and by
  370: scoped, revocable delegation with concentration visibility. The architecture
  371: does not assume attentive citizens; it assumes mostly inattentive ones and
  372: routes their weight through inspectable intermediation (Lupia and McCubbins
  373: 1998). This is a design answer to the citizen-competence objection in its
  374: sharpest contemporary form (Brennan 2016): rather than restricting anyone's right to participate, the architecture makes the intermediation that inattention
  375: produces visible, revocable, and auditable.
  376: 
  377: An apparent objection —that participating via app, wallet, and AI tutor
  378: excludes the non-digital population— dissolves under the comparative
  379: discipline: the non-digital citizen already delegates today, handing their
  380: decision, through the vote, to a distant representative who allocates the
  381: budget for them. Core v0 does not add a barrier: it removes a level of
  382: indirection. Whoever never participates falls to the system default —equal per
  383: citizen, mandate-bound—, not to the attentive minority's preference; and
  384: whoever participates even minimally, including through non-digital channels or
  385: assisted delegation, brings the decision closer to their direct interests
  386: through microdelegation and rules such as "near me" that fund what they can
  387: touch. What appears to exclude, includes more —with the construction of the
  388: planning scope as the only remaining indirection (Section 8).
  389: 
  390: **Transition.** Deployment proceeds through operating modes — closed,
  391: tutored, semi-open, open — in which a public authority may retain
  392: eligibility review (project admissibility), but every material tutored decision, and every
  393: tutored silence past its deadline, becomes a public governance-resolution
  394: object. Incumbent-resistance indicators (scope share opened, rejection and
  395: timeout rates, operator privilege) make symbolic adoption distinguishable
  396: from real transfer.
  397: 
  398: ## 5. Formal analysis
  399: 
  400: We state the three models and their results; proofs are one-step algebra and
  401: appear in the companion note ([formal-models](../research/formal-models.md)).
  402: All agents are risk-neutral; budgets are normalized to 1. The deterrence
  403: structure throughout is Becker's (1968): a violation is deterred when the
  404: detection probability times the stake at risk exceeds its gain — our
  405: contribution is mapping each term of that inequality onto a named,
  406: configurable architectural object. To avoid notation collisions, *Proposition
  407: N* denotes the formal results of this section; *P001/P007*, the methodological
  408: rules (§2); and *prediction N*, the behavioral predictions of §5.3.
  409: 
  410: ### 5.1 Milestone-gated disbursement
  411: 
  412: An executor chooses to deliver a milestone at private cost *c* ∈ (0, 1) or
  413: to divert. The mechanism releases an advance *a*, holds the remainder for
  414: reviewed acceptance, recovers a fraction *r* of the advance on confirmed
  415: non-delivery, seizes a posted guarantee *γ* (carrying cost *κ* per unit),
  416: and imposes a reputational continuation loss *R*. Review confirms diversion
  417: with probability *p* — the joint quality of evidence standards, fiscalizer
  418: independence, and corroboration.
  419: 
  420: **Proposition 1 (incentive compatibility).** Delivery is optimal iff
  421: 
  422: > *c* ≤ *p* · [ (1 − *a*(1 − *r*)) + *γ* + *R* ].
  423: 
  424: Delivery must be cheaper than the detection probability times the total
  425: stake at risk. Every disbursement-gaming test in the architecture is a term
  426: in this inequality.
  427: 
  428: **Proposition 2 (weak verification must be priced).** The minimal guarantee
  429: sustaining delivery for all *c* ≤ *c̄* is *γ\**(*p*) = max{0, *c̄*/*p* −
  430: (1 − *a*(1 − *r*)) − *R*}, decreasing and convex in *p*. Where verification
  431: is weak — thin fiscalization markets, poor evidence quality — the mechanism
  432: must compensate with smaller advances, more recoverability, larger
  433: guarantees, or higher-reputation executors. A single global guarantee
  434: percentage cannot be optimal across heterogeneous verification
  435: environments.
  436: 
  437: The deterrence terms of this condition are complements, not substitutes. A
  438: pre-registered ablation on the companion experiments (Offermann 2026b)
  439: measured the consequence: at the designed operating point the inequality
  440: holds with slack, so removing any single term costs almost nothing — and a
  441: deployment negotiated one defensible concession at a time can cross the
  442: threshold invisibly, ending below the status quo it replaced (0.87× verified
  443: value with selection quality intact) while looking fully instrumented. The
  444: corpus therefore requires every scope to publish its deterrence-inequality
  445: margin in its operating configuration, recomputed on every term change, with
  446: term reductions classified as material rule changes (docs/111). The same
  447: slack, kept intact, buys an unexpected dividend: it absorbs verification-
  448: instrument error — in the companion panel of five real model families, even
  449: a machine verifier passing ~20% of judgment-requiring fraud produced
  450: leakage indistinguishable from pure-human verification, because the cascade
  451: removes the attempts upstream — provided the adversary is not colluding
  452: across the verification layers (Offermann 2026b, docs/113).
  453: 
  454: **Proposition 3 (participation-deterrence trade-off).** Raising *γ* relaxes
  455: incentive compatibility at rate *p* but lowers honest executors' payoff at
  456: rate *κ*; under a designer objective weighing one unit of incentive slack
  457: equally against one unit of honest-executor payoff, a guarantee increase is
  458: net-beneficial only if *p* > *κ* (other weightings shift the threshold, not
  459: the trade-off's structure). Where detection quality is below the local cost
  460: of capital, piling on guarantees excludes honest low-margin executors
  461: without deterring fraud — the formal content of the architecture's
  462: proportionality discipline.
  463: 
  464: ### 5.2 Collusion-proof fiscalization
  465: 
  466: A non-delivered milestone is worth *G* to the executor if fraudulently
  467: approved. Release requires approval by *k* protocol-assigned fiscalizers,
  468: each carrying forfeitable stake *W* (future protocol fees plus role
  469: reputation) and facing post-approval discovery probability *q*. Because
  470: assignment is protocolized and repeat pairings are visible, executor and
  471: fiscalizer are strangers: a bribe offer is itself reported with probability
  472: *δ*, costing the executor penalty *P_e*.
  473: 
  474: **Proposition 4 (collusion-proofness).** Approval fraud is unsustainable if
  475: 
  476: > *k* · *q* · *W* ≥ *G* − (*δ* / (1 − *δ*)) · *P_e*,
  477: 
  478: and in particular whenever *kqW* ≥ *G*. Three corollaries carry design weight:
  479: 
  480: - ***Corroboration substitutes for reputation capital.*** The required stake
  481:   per fiscalizer falls linearly in *k*, so redundant review is exactly what
  482:   makes shallow-reputation fiscalizer pools workable, at linear control cost
  483:   —which is what proportional threshold policies are for.
  484: 
  485: - ***Repeat relationships are the attack surface.*** The friction term exists
  486:   only while relational contracting is prevented, which is why repeat-pairing
  487:   visibility is load-bearing (we hold the report probability *δ* exogenous to
  488:   *k*; endogenizing it —more approached reviewers, more chances of a report—
  489:   only strengthens the condition).
  490: 
  491: - ***Thin markets attack both models at once.*** A monopolist fiscalizer that
  492:   cannot credibly be excluded loses its forfeitable stake (*W* → 0) while also
  493:   degrading *p* in Proposition 1: the two conditions identify the same
  494:   environments as fragile, for the same reason.
  495: 
  496: ### 5.3 Attention-constrained allocation
  497: 
  498: Citizens allocate small individual budgets; the pivotal return to evaluating
  499: projects is negligible, so rational ignorance is the equilibrium (Downs
  500: 1957), and the design question is where the *inattentive* majority's weight
  501: flows: to salience amplified by social proof (Bikhchandani, Hirshleifer and
  502: Welch 1992; Salganik, Dodds and Watts 2006), or to the architecture's own
  503: default layer, whose routing follows the distributed project prioritization
  504: — the aggregated allocation profiles — not a central plan. The model yields three testable
  505: predictions — caps tame cascades (prediction 1), defaults anchor quality (prediction 2), decay
  506: degrades gracefully only with defaults (prediction 3) — evaluated next.
  507: 
  508: ## 6. Computational evidence
  509: 
  510: We test the three predictions of §5.3 —and, in successive experiments, the
  511: assumptions of Propositions 1–4— in an agent-based simulation. Each experiment
  512: (E1–E8) corresponds to a finding:
  513: 
  514: | Exp | What it tests | |
  515: |---|---|---|
  516: | E1 | do funding caps raise quality? | Finding 1 |
  517: | E2 | what carries allocation quality? | Finding 2 |
  518: | E3 | what buffers participation decay? | Finding 3 |
  519: | E4 | distributed aggregation vs. central construction (refined by a symmetric-frictions frontier + capture, E4-v4/v5) | Finding 4 |
  520: | E5 | where the architecture gains value (selection and delivery layers) | Finding 5 |
  521: | E6 | reputational competition and execution standard | Finding 6 |
  522: | E7 | comparison against an audit-parameterized baseline | Finding 7 |
  523: | E8 | robustness under endogenous behavioral participation | close of §6 |
  524: 
  525: We simulate 10,000 citizens over 24 monthly cycles allocating across a
  526: standing pool of 40 projects with quality *θ*, salience *s* (measured
  527: corr(*θ*, *s*) ≈ 0.24), prioritization need-weights *w* = λ*θ* + (1 − λ)*u*
  528: (where *u* is an idiosyncratic need component independent of quality) with
  529: mixing weight λ ∈ {0.4, 0.8} — measured corr(*θ*, *w*) ≈ 0.55 and ≈ 0.97
  530: respectively — and 3× scarcity (only a minority of projects can
  531: complete). Evaluators (2–10%) fund the best quality they sample; salience
  532: followers see a six-slot discovery surface ranked by salience amplified by
  533: funding progress; default followers' budget fills projects in planning-
  534: priority order. The funding-target closure rule is toggleable. Twenty
  535: seeded runs per condition; the code is dependency-free and deterministic
  536: (`scripts/simulation/allocation-sim.mjs`; full tables in
  537: [simulation-results](../research/simulation-results.md)).
  538: 
  539: **Status of the earlier compound ratios.** Three baselines of the same
  540: value-per-budget ratio were produced by this agent-based apparatus: **2.19×**
  541: against zero-control (E5), **2.22×** against the audit-parameterized status quo
  542: (E7), and **2.26×** under behavioral adoption (E8). They are retained here for
  543: traceability as **conditional outputs of that apparatus**, but are **superseded
  544: for magnitude inference** and are no longer offered as the paper's headline.
  545: 
  546: **Quantitative status (governing).** A pre-registered, symmetric, selection-only
  547: stress test — both arms with matched expected appraisal-report budgets, the same
  548: candidate pool, costs and noise, delivery at parity, each acting on its own noisy
  549: estimate rather than ground truth — found the distributed-minus-central selection
  550: advantage **positive in every one of 18 pre-specified cells but small.** The
  551: pre-registered decision statistic is the **pooled median Δ = 0.025**, below the
  552: pre-registered **0.05 research-program rebuild gate**; a **post-hoc** ratio-of-sums estimate is
  553: **Δ = 0.026, with a 95% world-cluster Monte-Carlo interval [0.023, 0.029]**
  554: (reported separately, on the simulated data-generating process). The compound
  555: multiplier is therefore **not** claimed as a calibrated effect. This is a stylized
  556: test of a *selection mechanism*, not a validated implementation of Core v0: its
  557: value and credit variables are abstract scores, not measured visibility,
  558: traceability, permanence, or public value. The **0.05** figure is a
  559: research-program **rebuild threshold** on this uncalibrated scale (a go/no-go rule
  560: for whether to pursue a quantitative rebuild), **not** a calibrated policy-materiality
  561: threshold. The controlling specification is
  562: [claim-and-estimand-contract](../research/claim-and-estimand-contract.md); the test,
  563: its frozen pre-registration, results, and diagnostics are
  564: `scripts/simulation/e5-sp-symmetry-gate.mjs` and `audits/2026-07-10/symmetry-gate-*`.
  565: The load-bearing contributions are the architecture and the mechanism *direction*,
  566: not a point multiplier.
  567: 
  568: **The symmetric credit-versus-coverage gate (methods and result).** Because this
  569: is the paper's one confirmatory computation, its design is stated in full here
  570: rather than only by reference. Each world holds K = 500 candidate projects; for
  571: each, N = 5000 potential participants are considered, each interested with a
  572: project-specific probability, so the interested reach is at most N and endogenous.
  573: Both arms then see the
  574: same candidate pool, the same exact costs, the same truth net[j] = S[j] − h·cost[j],
  575: delivery held at **parity**, and the same report noise report = v + Normal(0, τ);
  576: each funds a **greedy** set under a budget of one-third of total project cost, is
  577: eligible to fund a project only where *its own* noisy estimate of net is positive
  578: (no oracle gate), and its delivered value is scored on the projects' *true* net.
  579: The arms are symmetric except for the coverage mechanism and its matched
  580: counterparts. *Distributed (endogenous coverage):* each interested citizen reports
  581: independently with probability p if her value v ≥ 0 and p·(1 − β) if v < 0 (adverse
  582: voice bias), giving ĥS_D = Σreports / p, ranked by estimated net per cost.
  583: *Central (competent value-reader):* an appraisal budget matched to the distributed
  584: arm's *expected* total reports in that world, spread **evenly** across projects as a
  585: rounded fixed per-project bandwidth m_C = round(expected reports / K) (so the two
  586: arms' appraisal totals are equal in expectation up to that rounding); per project it
  587: samples m_C interested citizens, observes v + Normal(0, τ), and forms its own noisy
  588: ĥNet_C = reach·mean(observed) − h·cost. It ranks by score = (1 − λ)·z(ĥNet_C/cost) + λ·z(P/cost) — its **own noisy
  589: estimate**, never the true net — where P is claimable political credit (the
  590: electoral credit-claiming and traceability logic by which visible, attributable
  591: benefits are favoured over diffuse ones; Mayhew 1974; Arnold 1990) and λ is bounded
  592: credit pressure (a *posited* pressure whose real-world magnitude must be measured,
  593: not assumed). Credit moves *ranking*, never eligibility (no knowingly
  594: value-destroying planner). The legitimate asymmetries are therefore only these:
  595: distributed reports self-route to projects citizens care about while negative
  596: stakeholders participate less, and central appraisal is spread evenly while its
  597: ranking carries credit pressure — everything else is shared. The estimand is
  598: **Δ = (D − C)/O** per world, where D, C, O are delivered true net for the
  599: distributed, central, and full-information greedy arms and O is a reference level,
  600: not an optimum. The frozen grid sweeps λ ∈ {0, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3} (λ = 0 a negative
  601: control), a latent-correlation setting ρ ∈ {0, 0.5, 1} (realized corr(S, P) ≈ 0.00,
  602: 0.30, 0.82), and h ∈ {1.5, 2.5, 4} over 100 seeded worlds, in a baseline
  603: observation regime (p = .35, β = .30, τ = .5) and a matched-budget low-information
  604: stress regime (p = .15, β = .60, τ = 1.0). The **pre-registered decision rule** —
  605: frozen before running and designed by the independent auditor to be adversarial —
  606: required, for a GO on rebuilding the quantitative engine, at least 15 of the 18
  607: primary cells with mean Δ > 0, a pooled **median Δ ≥ 0.05**, a bootstrap lower
  608: bound > 0, and median Δ ≥ 0 under the stress regime, plus a guard to pause if the
  609: λ = 0 control itself exceeded 0.05. The result was **NO-GO**: the advantage was
  610: positive in all 18 primary cells, but the pre-registered pooled **median Δ = 0.025**,
  611: below the 0.05 rebuild gate; the λ = 0 negative control sat at ≈ 0.016, within the
  612: pause guard (no hidden asymmetry flagged). A **post-hoc** world-cluster
  613: ratio-of-sums estimate was Δ = 0.026 [0.023, 0.029] (Monte-Carlo uncertainty on the
  614: simulated data-generating process, reported separately from the median). The
  615: advantage rises with credit pressure λ and falls as credit aligns with value — the
  616: credit-versus-coverage mechanism — but it is small, which is why the calibrated
  617: multiplier is retired and the paper rests on the architecture and the mechanism
  618: direction.
  619: 
  620: **Finding 1: funding caps are an anti-concentration device, not a quality
  621: device.** With closure ON, concentration falls (funding Gini 0.732 vs
  622: 0.759), the most salient 5% of projects absorb less (16.8% vs 19.6% of all
  623: funding), and 15% more projects complete (25.3% vs 21.9%). But quality
  624: selection is unchanged (*sel(θ)*, the Pearson correlation across projects between
  625: latent quality θ and the binary indicator that a project reaches its funding
  626: target, ≈ 0.39 vs 0.41): the truncated surplus
  627: spills to the next most *visible* project, not the next *best* one. The
  628: architecture's claim for the closure rule should be — and in the corpus now
  629: is — bounded accordingly.
  630: 
  631: **Finding 2: the default anchor, not citizen attention, carries allocation
  632: quality.** A default-anchored mix, with a near-perfectly informed planner (r ≈
  633: 0.97), reaches sel(θ) ≈ 0.71: between 1.6× and 2× the salience-driven
  634: configurations (≈ 0.35–0.43). Quintupling citizen attention (α from 2% to
  635: 10%), by contrast, barely moves the needle —at most ≈ 0.08 in salience-driven
  636: regimes, and essentially nothing in default-anchored ones—, while degrading
  637: the vector's informational quality from near-perfect to moderate (r ≈ 0.97 →
  638: 0.55) costs ≈ 0.29 of selection. The anchor rules, not attention.
  639: 
  640: Two qualifications keep the finding honest:
  641: 
  642: - **By construction.** The default rule is a deterministic θ-correlated
  643:   allocator already holding most of the budget; what is measured is the
  644:   *conditioning* —how much the vector's informational quality determines the
  645:   anchor's value, and how little attention substitutes for it—, not the wisdom
  646:   of the crowd.
  647: 
  648: - **Robustness.** A sensitivity panel (varying evaluator sample size and
  649:   social-proof strength) shows the regime ordering is robust, except under
  650:   very strong social proof, where the regimes converge within noise because
  651:   strong amplification also propagates the evaluators' quality signal.
  652:   Magnitudes are parameter-dependent and uncalibrated; what survives all
  653:   variations is the ordering and the dominance of the prioritization's
  654:   informational quality.
  655: 
  656: This finding quantifies the leverage concentrated in whatever constructs the
  657: project prioritization the passive share follows. That prioritization has two
  658: layers —which a companion study (Offermann 2026b) separated for the first
  659: time—: the macro categorization (this corpus's Planning Scope, which frames
  660: eligibility and carries no budget weights) and the aggregated allocation
  661: profiles that route budget within it. The distributed arm is robust to the
  662: quality of that categorization and a central arm is fragile to it, so the
  663: advantage over a central status quo is not fixed: it grows as central planning
  664: worsens — a model-internal direction the companion apparatus illustrates (a
  665: conditional contrast rising from roughly twofold to more than fivefold, not a
  666: calibrated multiplier; see the quantitative-status note in this section).
  667: 
  668: Two architectural facts scope the statement and forestall a tempting
  669: over-reading. First, the default layer is pluggable, not mandatorily central:
  670: the civic autopilot gives each citizen manual allocation, delegation,
  671: published allocation profiles, a personal automatic rule, or the system
  672: default; an onboarding citizen must explicitly select or acknowledge a base
  673: profile, and only the share who never engage necessarily follows the system
  674: default —which itself operates under a recorded allocation mandate. Second,
  675: centralized construction of scope weights is a property of the closed and
  676: tutored transition modes, not of the architecture: operating modes are
  677: country-configured states, and the designed trajectory is toward open
  678: construction (Finding 4 measures its in-model viability).
  679: 
  680: The numbers therefore establish a conditional. The binding constraint on
  681: allocation quality is the informational quality of the **project
  682: prioritization the passive share follows** —the aggregated allocation
  683: profiles, not a macro planning vector—, whoever or whatever supplies it. A
  684: captured or ignorant supplier is the failure mode; a well-informed or
  685: well-aggregated one, the asset. Randomizing that prioritization to escape
  686: capture does not help: it buys neutrality at the price of near-random quality
  687: for the passive share. And because the architecture's designed trajectory
  688: distributes its construction (open mode) and keeps it visible, versioned, and
  689: pluggable, the constraint is met by distribution, not by a central agenda.
  690: This is distinct from the narrower agenda-setting point of Section 8, which
  691: concerns only who frames eligibility.
  692: 
  693: E1–E3 do not authorize two readings: the prioritization's origin is
  694: unspecified (r is a property of the vector, not of a state office), and the
  695: modeled crowd carries social proof but no knowledge —so these experiments
  696: compare attention against weight quality, not central against distributed
  697: knowledge. Finding 4 makes that comparison properly.
  698: 
  699: **Finding 3: what buffers participation decay is the anchor's level, not
  700: where the leavers' weight flows — our own prediction failed here.** We
  701: predicted that decaying active evaluation (10% to 2% over 24 cycles) would
  702: degrade allocation gracefully only if the released share flowed to
  703: defaults rather than salience. Exploiting common seeds across conditions,
  704: the paired analysis rejects this: the destination's effect on overall
  705: selection is null at both anchor strengths (mean paired differences 0.001
  706: [−0.031, 0.033] and 0.021 [−0.028, 0.071]), and the only interval
  707: excluding zero is small and opposite-signed (at a strong anchor, the
  708: salience destination preserves late-cycle alignment slightly better —
  709: plausibly because amplified social proof also propagates evaluator
  710: seeding). What governs robustness to decay is the structural share of the
  711: default layer itself, Finding 2's variable. Engagement decay — the
  712: documented fate of civic-tech participation (Hirschman 1970; Peixoto and
  713: Fox 2016) — is a
  714: buffered risk here, but the buffer is the institutional layer's size, and
  715: within-cycle quality alignment still erodes in later cycles under all
  716: conditions, so decay is bought, not free.
  717: 
  718: **Finding 4: aggregated dispersed signals outperform fixed-bandwidth
  719: central construction of the weight vector — but a fair, symmetric
  720: re-examination resolves the advantage into a conditional frontier and adds a
  721: capture-resistance that guards it.** A fourth, pre-registered experiment
  722: (design and predictions committed before any run;
  723: `research/e4-institutional-knowledge-design.md`) models knowledge
  724: symmetrically instead of endowing it: a planner with fixed bandwidth
  725: (thirty deep inspections; its correlation with latent quality is now
  726: measured output, collapsing 0.81 → 0.37 → 0.17 as the project pool grows
  727: 40 → 200 → 1000) against thirty percent of citizens holding four
  728: individually poor local signals each (noise 0.35). Five regimes share the
  729: identical world and signals and differ only in the aggregation
  730: institution. The pre-registered scale-crossover prediction failed in the
  731: informative direction: open construction of the weight vector — a plain
  732: average of citizen signals per project — beats pure central construction
  733: at *every* scale, including the smallest, where the planner inspects
  734: three-quarters of the world (sel(θ) 0.76 vs 0.62 at N = 40; 0.73 vs 0.04
  735: at N = 1000). Twelve thousand noisy signals average into a near-perfect
  736: vector; thirty good inspections cannot compete, and fixed central
  737: bandwidth decays toward randomness as the world grows — a Condorcet
  738: (1785) aggregation logic, and we treat it as such: the jury theorem's
  739: known failure conditions (Austen-Smith and Banks 1996) define exactly
  740: the boundary the seventh experiment tests. Three
  741: qualifications carry the finding's honest weight. First, the same
  742: dispersed knowledge *without* an aggregation institution is wasted: the
  743: uncoordinated regime funds 0.6–15% of projects and selects poorly — the
  744: result vindicates aggregation mechanisms, not the absence of mechanism,
  745: and Core v0's default-plus-closure layer is exactly such a mechanism.
  746: Second, aggregation defeats noise, not bias: signals are unbiased by
  747: construction, and a common-mode bias uncorrelated with quality
  748: (misinformation, expressive allocation) would not average out — only
  749: endogenous social-proof contamination was tested, and proved largely
  750: benign because visible funding progress is itself quality-correlated in a
  751: well-anchored system. Third, elicitation is non-strategic by assumption;
  752: in deployment, signal reporting becomes a gaming and clientelism surface,
  753: and the mechanics of open scope construction remain a gated design
  754: problem. Within those bounds, the finding points in a clear direction: the binding variable is not who holds the pen but how much
  755: dispersed information the scope-construction institution ingests.
  756: 
  757: The simulation also disciplines rhetoric — in both directions. Nothing in
  758: E1–E3 supports describing Core v0 allocation as "the wisdom of crowds":
  759: the honest description is *inspectable intermediation with a
  760: citizen-correctable default*, which the results show is both realistic and
  761: better than the salience-driven alternative that unstructured platforms
  762: converge to. And nothing in E1–E3 licenses the opposite reading — that
  763: central planning knowledge beats distributed knowledge — because they
  764: never modeled distributed knowledge; when E4 does, aggregation wins
  765: wherever its named preconditions hold. Both discourses lose their slogan;
  766: the design keeps its numbers.
  767: 
  768: *A fair, symmetric re-examination (E4-v4/v5).* This first-pass E4 gave the
  769: central a fixed inspection bandwidth and left citizen signals unbiased — two
  770: idealizations that, an adversarial review showed, tilt the comparison in the
  771: distributed arm's favor. A rebuilt model
  772: (`scripts/simulation/e4-v4-symmetric-frontier.mjs`,
  773: `research/e4-v4-symmetric-frontier-results.txt`, `research/e4-v5-capture-design.md`)
  774: gives *both* institutions a symmetric friction in perceiving true value,
  775: including harm: the central attenuates perceived harm by a coefficient η (0 =
  776: blind to diffuse harm, 1 = a fully accountable planner), while the distributed
  777: reads true valuations but the diffusely harmed under-participate at a rate β
  778: (voice inequality). The result is not a multiplier but a frontier with a
  779: closed-form parity locus (`research/e4-analytical-backbone.md`): both
  780: institutions are biased estimators of the same Samuelson value T = S⁺ − S⁻,
  781: ranking projects by S⁺ − θ·S⁻ with θ_C = η and θ_D = 1 − β, so the distributed
  782: dominates exactly when its coefficient is closer to the true harm-weight of one
  783: — i.e. **β < 1 − η**. The simulation confirms the law (parity on the
  784: anti-diagonal η + β = 1) and quantifies the delivered-value degradation off it
  785: (rough parity to ~1.8× as a **distributed-to-central ratio** across the plausible
  786: box — this is D/C, not a fraction of the full-information benchmark). The advantage
  787: is thus a property of *including the harmed*, not of aggregation per se; it reaches
  788: parity along the anti-diagonal β = 1 − η and turns into a central win below it
  789: (β > 1 − η) — which absorbs the participation-bias objection into the model's own
  790: β axis rather than leaving it external. Neither
  791: extreme is assumed: η is *swept*, not fixed, and a low but non-zero η is a
  792: defended regime, not a premise. The diffuse-harm literature (Bastiat's unseen
  793: costs; Olson's asymmetric organization on contested issues; Wilson's
  794: client-politics quadrant; Scott's legibility) describes *when* diffuse costs go
  795: unrepresented — each read at its proper scope, not as a claim of global
  796: blindness — while the opposing thesis that political competition disciplines the
  797: centre toward efficiency (Wittman 1989) holds weakest in exactly that
  798: client-politics quadrant. Empirically, most *measured* procurement loss is
  799: passive — incompetence, not theft (Bandiera, Prat and Valletti 2009) —
  800: consistent with a low but non-zero η.
  801: 
  802: *Capture-resistance guards the advantage (E4-v5).* Modelling organized capture
  803: symmetrically — the review's hardest objection, applied in fairness to the
  804: central planner too — the asymmetry widens rather than closes. A group captures
  805: a low-value project only when its private rent exceeds acquisition cost plus the
  806: expected sanction (Becker 1968); with the deterrence asymmetry carried entirely
  807: by detection probability and acquisition scaling (the penalty held equal,
  808: conservatively), the status quo turns net-harmful at rents near 10% of project
  809: cost while the distributed threshold — floored by the equal-per-citizen wallet,
  810: which money can persuade but cannot buy — sits roughly ten times higher (closed
  811: form ρ(C) in the backbone note). Detection is a snowball p = 1 − (1 − q)^m, so
  812: its floor is an expected m·q ≥ −ln(1 − p_c) ≈ 0.1 reporters drawn from the
  813: transparent affected public — low, but this is a model-internal statement whose
  814: force depends entirely on the stipulated detection gap (central ~0.10 vs
  815: distributed ~1.0), not an empirical burden-of-proof: sensitivity analysis is
  816: decisive here — the distributed advantage narrows and can reverse if distributed
  817: detection is driven down toward ~0.3, so the claim is that organized recapture is
  818: harder under the distributed arm's transparency *given these parameters*, not that
  819: it is ruled out. This ties Finding
  820: 4 to the integrity layer of Finding 5: the same fiscalization that makes value
  821: arrive is what keeps the allocation advantage from being bought back by
  822: organized rents, so the two are a layer and its safeguard rather than
  823: independent multipliers. Every magnitude here is model-internal; the literature
  824: (Olson, Wilson, Scott, Bastiat; Becker, Becker and Stigler, Stokes,
  825: Dyck-Morse-Zingales; Ostrom's self-monitoring commons) defends the direction,
  826: the mechanism, and the sign of the asymmetry — not the numbers.
  827: 
  828: *Analytical backbone.* Three closed forms carry the weight, each verified against
  829: the simulation (`research/e4-analytical-backbone.md`); the runs then only confirm
  830: them and quantify the degradation off the clean cases. **(i) The parity law.**
  831: Writing each institution as a biased estimator that ranks projects by S⁺ − θ·S⁻,
  832: the central keeps θ_C = η of perceived harm and the distributed reveals
  833: θ_D = 1 − β (the participation rate cancels from the ranking); since the true
  834: harm-weight is one, the distributed arm delivers more true value **iff
  835: β < 1 − η**, parity on the anti-diagonal. A bias–variance reading would predict
  836: that on the parity line, where the bias cancels, the lower-variance estimator wins —
  837: the distributed's revelation noise is zero (a funder knows her own value), the
  838: central's proxy noise is not. The implemented simulation does **not** bear this out
  839: at the accountable corner: at (η = 1, β = 0) the measured ratio is **0.89× — a
  840: central win (D/C < 1)** — so the honest reading is the noise-free parity law
  841: β = 1 − η, and the bias–variance tilt toward the distributed is not supported there.
  842: **(ii) The capture
  843: threshold.** From rent > acquisition + P(detect)·penalty, the central's threshold
  844: λ\*_C = (k_c + p_c·f)/C falls toward zero as its detection shrinks, while the
  845: distributed's λ\*_D = k_d + p_d·f/C is *floored* by the equal-wallet acquisition
  846: term k_d; the resistance ratio ρ(C) = (k_d·C + p_d·f)/(k_c + p_c·f) ≈ 6–10×,
  847: rising in project cost. **(iii) The detection floor.** With snowball detection
  848: P = 1 − (1 − q)^m, beating a central rate p_c needs, in the small-*q* (Poisson)
  849: approximation (1 − q)^m ≈ e^{−m·q}, only an expected m·q ≥ −ln(1 − p_c) ≈ 0.1
  850: reporters — the exact Bernoulli condition is m ≥ ln(1 − p_c)/ln(1 − q), which
  851: depends on *m* and *q* separately, not only on their product. It is a
  852: model-internal detection floor under the stipulated parameters
  853: (sensitivity-dependent; see Finding 4), not an empirical burden-of-proof inversion.
  854: Three invariances bound the arbitrary-magnitudes worry — as properties of the
  855: noise-free, large-set *expectation*, not of every finite-sample run: the advantage
  856: is invariant to the units of value (scale); in expectation it depends on the
  857: voice-bias β rather than on the participation *level* (though in finite samples
  858: turnout changes sample size, sampling variance, and hence rankings and
  859: portfolios); and, because only the first moments S⁺, S⁻ enter the expected
  860: ranking, the Gaussian valuation draw is a convenience there rather than a
  861: load-bearing assumption (finite-sample tails and valuation shape can still move
  862: rankings). One honest boundary the runs mark: the parity law is the large-set
  863: limit; when a project's interested set is very small — a handful of people — the
  864: distributed's sampling variance dominates and a full-census central regains the
  865: edge. Two further boundaries are honest to state. The comparison is *static* — a
  866: single allocation round — whereas real harms surface over iterated cycles and
  867: feed back through elections and audit, so a persistently blind centre is the
  868: stress case, not an inevitability. And the distributed arm is *scored on the true
  869: value it reveals*, which would be circular were it not that the β voice-bias and
  870: the capture frictions make its revealed signal a biased, contestable estimate of
  871: that value rather than a definitional one.
  872: 
  873: *Positioning.* The first-best preference-aggregation mechanism —
  874: Vickrey–Clarke–Groves — is infeasible for public budgets (it is not
  875: budget-balanced; Green and Laffont 1979), so both the central planner and Core v0
  876: are *second-best* institutions (Lipsey and Lancaster 1956); the comparison asks
  877: which second-best delivers more, not whether either is optimal. Core v0
  878: accordingly claims not strategy-proofness — impossible for any non-dictatorial
  879: mechanism (Gibbard 1973; Satterthwaite 1975) — but *capture-resistance under
  880: bounded organized coordination*. The equal-per-citizen wallet places it in the
  881: intensity-expressing voting family (Casella 2012; Lalley and Weyl 2018) with a
  882: sharper anti-plutocratic property: it caps influence by *equal endowment* rather
  883: than by convex pricing, so money can persuade wallet-holders but cannot buy
  884: wallets — exactly the acquisition-cost floor k_d of the capture threshold.
  885: Finally, the aggregation advantage is the Condorcet (1785) jury logic and dies
  886: under its independence condition (Austen-Smith and Banks 1996): organized capture
  887: is the correlated-error violation of that independence, so the integrity layer
  888: exists precisely to defend the assumption on which distributed aggregation rests.
  889: The value primitive follows Sen's capabilities for *what* is aggregated —
  890: freedoms, not money-utility — while the *summation* rests on Samuelson (1954), an
  891: aggregation Sen himself resists; we invoke each only where it applies.
  892: 
  893: *Calibration.* The magnitudes are model-internal, but the gap to data is a
  894: roadmap, not an apology. The central's 46–68% of benchmark-achievable value is a
  895: **candidate validation target requiring an explicit construct mapping** — not a
  896: direct check: the ex-post realized-to-appraised ratio (the World Bank's Independent
  897: Evaluation Group ratings; Flyvbjerg, Bruzelius and Rothengatter 2003) is a
  898: *different construct* from central selection relative to a full-information
  899: benchmark, so bridging them needs a stated mapping before either can calibrate the
  900: other; the voice bias β can likewise be anchored to measured
  901: participatory-budgeting demographics rather than assumed. And independent field
  902: evidence points the direction the model does: participatory budgeting in Brazil
  903: shifted spending toward sanitation and health and lowered infant mortality at
  904: constant per-capita budget (Gonçalves 2014) — a real-world instance of
  905: citizen-directed allocation delivering more real value, cleanly separable from
  906: any magnitude the model reports. The calibration-targets appendix makes the
  907: model-internal / data boundary a visible line.
  908: 
  909: **Finding 5: delivered value, not allocation, is where the architecture
  910: earns its keep — and selection and delivery interact.** A fifth,
  911: pre-registered experiment (`research/e5-value-delivery-design.md`) adds
  912: the execution stage the first four omitted: executors with hidden types
  913: whose diversion decision follows Proposition 1's incentive condition,
  914: under an opaque delivery regime — a zero-control lower bound (low
  915: detection, unprotected advances, no recovery, no reputational memory),
  916: with parameters inside the empirically documented leakage band: 87% in
  917: Uganda's capitation grants (Reinikka and Svensson 2004), 24% in
  918: Indonesian roads (Olken 2007) — versus the verified regime built from
  919: Propositions 1-4 (milestone gating, retention, recovery, evidence-layer
  920: detection, and a reputational stake: a visible confirmed-diversion record
  921: that costs future selection by funders).
  922: Crossing delivery with the two E4 selection regimes yields a 2×2 whose
  923: main effects are two plain questions. Same projects, different control
  924: layer: the verified regime delivers +43% on identical portfolios
  925: (paired ΔV = 0.168 [0.143, 0.193]), and the zero-control regime's
  926: official completion overstates its real delivery by twenty-nine
  927: percentage points. Same control layer, different
  928: projects: social prioritization delivers +53-54% under either regime.
  929: The interaction is positive and significant (+0.085 [0.053, 0.117]): within
  930: this apparatus the two layers **interact rather than merely add**, yielding a
  931: **conditional zero-control scenario output of 2.19×** per unit of budget
  932: (0.859 vs 0.393) across direct-participation rates from 3% (the
  933: participatory-budgeting floor) to 40% (voting-scale). This compound is a
  934: model-internal factorial contrast, **not** a calibrated effect (see the
  935: quantitative-status note in Section 6 and the estimand contract). Two
  936: pre-registered predictions failed honestly.
  937: The expected dominance of delivery over selection did not hold at this
  938: scale — central selection at two hundred projects is near-random (E4),
  939: inflating the selection margin — so within this apparatus the robust pattern is
  940: the *interaction* of the two layers, not their ranking (the compound magnitude
  941: itself is retired as a calibrated effect; see Section 6). And the expected
  942: reputational cleansing never fired
  943: under the strong verification parameters, for the best possible reason:
  944: the incentive condition holds for every executor, so no one diverts and
  945: there is no one to exclude — deterrence pre-empts punishment, Becker's
  946: enforcement working ex ante. A labeled post-hoc sensitivity with weakened
  947: verification shows the second line of defense: partial deterrence,
  948: active detection, and an executor pool that measurably improves as
  949: funders stop selecting confirmed diverters, whose records are visible
  950: (opportunist share 0.28 → 0.21 over twenty-four cycles) — pool exit by
  951: lost preference, not by any platform exclusion power; reputation informs
  952: choices, it never excludes. A companion sweep of default discovery categories
  953: shows each carries a large, measurable distributional signature —
  954: near-me concentrates 71% of budget in the densest quintile, rural
  955: inverts it — so the default is a visible, configurable distributional
  956: policy lever, not an inherent planner bias.
  957: 
  958: **Finding 6: visibility sustains the standard; naive reputation markets
  959: concentrate faster than they select.** A sixth pre-registered experiment
  960: (`research/e6-reputational-competition-design.md`) isolates the incentive
  961: channel from deterrence entirely — a career-concerns setting in
  962: Holmström's (1999) sense: an all-honest executor pool with adjustable
  963: effort and no possibility of diversion (the model prices no explicit
  964: effort cost; cost-minimization is encoded behaviorally as the opaque
  965: regime's decay rule). In the opaque regime,
  966: effort collapses toward cost-minimization (0.49 → 0.24 over twenty-four
  967: cycles) — not through malice, but because effort has no return and no
  968: visible standard exists to imitate. Making verified quality visible
  969: sustains effort near its starting level, and the visible-competitive
  970: regime delivers +11% over the opaque baseline — a pure incentive gain
  971: with zero diversion in the model. Two pre-registered predictions failed
  972: informatively. Visibility alone carries most of the effect: the mirror
  973: precedes the market (the behavioral rule ties imitation to visibility, so
  974: part of this is by construction — but the construction encodes the claim
  975: that opacity erodes professional norms by removing the standard itself).
  976: And naive reputation-weighted assignment concentrates work dramatically
  977: (assignment Gini 0.84 versus 0.34) while tracking true ability only
  978: weakly — early-luck lock-in, the cumulative-advantage dynamic of
  979: information cascades reappearing in the executor market. The design
  980: lesson runs in both directions: verified visibility is where the quality
  981: incentive lives, and any strong reputation weighting — human or
  982: algorithmic — needs the concentration observability, entrant floors, and
  983: opportunity-normalized reputation the corpus prescribes. In Core v0,
  984: reputation informs funders' choices rather than automatic assignment,
  985: with concentration visible by construction — and it never excludes: no
  986: protocol rule bars a funder from choosing any admissible actor on
  987: reputational grounds.
  988: 
  989: **Finding 7: an audit-parameterized baseline — what it does and does not
  990: calibrate.** The manuscript-review round's sharpest attack held that the zero-control
  991: baseline is a caricature — real administrations run audit institutions,
  992: retentions, bonds, and inspection — and the answer was a seventh
  993: pre-registered experiment (`research/e7-calibrated-baseline-design.md`)
  994: with a committed withdrawal condition: if the headline collapsed against
  995: a fair baseline, it would be withdrawn, not requalified. The
  996: audit-parameterized status-quo arm draws its parameters from published
  997: audit-institution findings (a documented-practice-informed scenario;
  998: verification of some primary sources is ongoing) — detection from Chile's comptroller works
  999: studies, retention from documented payment-state practice, recovery from
 1000: Mexico's ASF series, leakage anchors category-matched to construction
 1001: (Olken 2007; the multi-country evidence base spans the U.S. GAO, the U.K. NAO, the
 1002: European Court of Auditors, Brazil's TCU and CGU, and the comptrollers
 1003: of Chile, Peru and Colombia; Ferraz and Finan 2008) — with the planner's
 1004: inspection bandwidth scaled to scope and coordinated signal bias swept
 1005: as the Condorcet failure regime. The withdrawal condition was not
 1006: triggered *within this apparatus*: against the audit-parameterized baseline it
 1007: produced 2.22× [2.10, 2.35] per unit of budget at scale, and
 1008: 1.4–1.6× at municipal pilot scale (10-40 projects), where central
 1009: selection with full coverage is competitive and the case rests on
 1010: delivery and metering. But the audit evidence *parameterizes the baseline's
 1011: leak*; it does **not** calibrate the Core v0 institutional treatment effect,
 1012: which is governed by the later pre-registered symmetric test (Section 6) whose
 1013: pre-registered pooled median selection advantage is Δ = 0.025 of a
 1014: full-information benchmark — so these E7 figures are retained as conditional
 1015: apparatus outputs, not a surviving headline. Within this apparatus, and
 1016: conditional on its stipulated opportunist-cost distribution and no-memory
 1017: baseline, one qualitative result is instructive: at the model's audit-reported
 1018: detection intensity (primary-source verification ongoing), without reputational
 1019: memory, the model deters no diversion — the audit-parameterized regime's incentive threshold lies
 1020: below every modelled opportunist's cost, so its leak equals the zero-control
 1021: regime's, and in the model the added detection reduces the visibility gap (from
 1022: twenty-nine to nineteen points) rather than raising delivered value. These are
 1023: model-internal outputs of E7's stipulated apparatus, not an estimated causal
 1024: effect of real-world auditing. The audit-parameterized arm's leak lands inside
 1025: the audit-reported leakage band (24-48% in works); the model's leak mechanics, fed
 1026: audit parameters, are *consistent with* the documented range — this parameterizes
 1027: the baseline's leak, it does not calibrate the institutional treatment effect. And the bias
 1028: sweep bounds the open-construction claim honestly: distributed
 1029: selection degrades near-linearly with coordinated signal capture and
 1030: crosses below a competent full-coverage municipal planner only at
 1031: roughly a thirty percent coordinated share — it degrades, never
 1032: collapses, and remains superior everywhere below ten percent.
 1033: 
 1034: A pre-registered eighth experiment (E8,
 1035: `research/e8-behavioral-participation-design.md`) then replaced the
 1036: participation side of these arms — the default share and informed share
 1037: the architecture arms had imposed — with adoption trajectories generated
 1038: by a companion behavioral study: a Core v0-conformant agent-based model
 1039: of awareness, registration, participation modes, and trusted
 1040: microdelegation, calibrated with LLM-elicited synthetic priors
 1041: (replication package: the distributed-governance-experiments
 1042: repository). The earlier apparatus produced 2.26 [2.23, 2.30] at scale under its
 1043: synthetic adoption assumptions and 2.15–2.9× across three populations and all
 1044: scales, including a launch trajectory that begins near zero
 1045: participation — which costs 1.7% of the ratio, because the default layer
 1046: anchors the thin early cycles by construction. The behavioral study also
 1047: independently reproduces the informed-share assumption these experiments
 1048: had imposed: 0.309 emergent against the 0.30 assumed.
 1049: 
 1050: **What survives.** Stripped to what the governing test supports: (1) under the
 1051: pre-registered symmetric gate the distributed selection advantage is *positive but
 1052: small* (median Δ = 0.025, below the 0.05 rebuild gate; NO-GO); (2) the load-bearing
 1053: contributions are the architecture and the qualitative credit-versus-coverage
 1054: mechanism — credit-pressured central ranking underweights diffuse value that
 1055: coverage-based distributed selection surfaces; (3) every compound ratio above
 1056: (2.19×/2.22×/2.26×, +43%, +53–54%, ~2×–5×) is a conditional, model-internal
 1057: apparatus output, not a calibrated effect; and (4) any calibrated total delivered-
 1058: value effect — selection *and* delivery, on real data — remains future work.
 1059: 
 1060: ## 7. Adversarial review as method
 1061: 
 1062: The architecture was developed under a documented adversarial loop:
 1063: **attack** (a brief stating a failure mode, its location in the corpus, a
 1064: stress scenario, and literature anchors) → **paired defense** (an objective
 1065: evaluation classifying the attack as founded, partially founded, or a
 1066: difference of judgment, with line-anchored citations into the corpus) →
 1067: **resolution** (an accepted document that either integrates a mechanism or
 1068: bounds the risk) → **propagation** (the resolution's constraints threaded
 1069: through every affected architecture document). The loop ran five rounds, all
 1070: resolved; every resolution is propagated through the corpus except the
 1071: manuscript-review round's four paired defenses (D037–D040), which carry accepted
 1072: resolutions whose remaining corpus propagation is tracked in the remediation
 1073: roadmap. The first round: eighteen attacks on
 1074: the architecture's mechanisms (metric gaming, fiscalizer capture,
 1075: disbursement gaming, collusion, related-party control, complexity,
 1076: incumbent resistance, among others). The second: fifteen deliberately
 1077: deeper attacks on the political and behavioral foundations (democratic
 1078: mandate, agenda-setting, fiscal dependence, thin markets, meta-governance
 1079: vacuum, rational ignorance, cascades, clientelism, polarization,
 1080: intertemporal myopia, the problem of many hands (Thompson 1980)). The
 1081: third round emerged
 1082: from the method turned outward: a simulated five-profile external review
 1083: of this paper's companion document generated reviewer questions the corpus
 1084: could not answer with existing anchors, and the standing rule converted
 1085: the two serious ones into formal attacks — the legal characterization of
 1086: the citizen allocation act, and the administrative capacity cost of
 1087: tutored operation — both since resolved and propagated. The fourth round
 1088: turned the same instrument on this manuscript itself: five simulated
 1089: reviewer profiles (academic, public law, systems architecture,
 1090: public-sector practice, educated general reader) attacked the published
 1091: v1.6, and their five unanswerable objections became formal attacks, each
 1092: now resolved — the zero-control baseline as a calibration strawman
 1093: (answered by the seventh experiment and a binding reporting rule), the
 1094: reserve of law over the allocation competence (an enabling-norm record
 1095: gating binding mode), reputational exclusion as an unprocessed sanction
 1096: (reclassified: the design holds no exclusion power to sanction with),
 1097: allocation traceability against preference secrecy (resolved as citizen
 1098: allocation secrecy with public money), and the adoption paradox (an
 1099: adoption layer under an explicit thesis boundary). The fifth round was an
 1100: ablation round of three attacks (A041–A043): the piecewise deployment of the
 1101: deterrence stack, the unregulated budget-release valve, and the verification
 1102: layer under machine-and-ring collusion — each resolved and propagated
 1103: (`docs/111`–`docs/113`). The method's
 1104: honesty requirement applies to itself: several resolutions answer their
 1105: attacks with an explicit "bounded, not solved," and the full review record
 1106: is public.
 1107: 
 1108: The loop terminates by the integrate-or-bound rule (P007). Its output
 1109: discipline is what distinguishes it from ordinary threat modeling: every
 1110: bounded attack must leave three artifacts — an explicit boundary sentence
 1111: ("Core v0 does not require X"), a visible residual risk, and a one-sentence
 1112: limitation statement. The limitations section below is therefore not a
 1113: gesture of humility; it is the accumulated, adversarially generated output
 1114: of the method. Of the forty-three attacks, none was dismissed; nine of
 1115: the second round's fifteen were classified founded outright and the other
 1116: six partially founded, all five of the manuscript round were classified
 1117: founded at least in part, and the corpus's answer to several is an honest
 1118: "bounded, not solved."
 1119: 
 1120: We used the loop with a single design team plus AI assistance — which is
 1121: why we call it structured self-critique rather than validation; a
 1122: self-administered adversary, however disciplined, cannot substitute for
 1123: independent attack. Its obvious next application is with genuinely
 1124: independent reviewers, which we identify below as the first item of
 1125: future work.
 1126: 
 1127: ## 8. Limitations
 1128: 
 1129: Stated per the method's own rule — each is a recorded boundary with a named
 1130: residual risk.
 1131: 
 1132: **Constructing the eligibility frame is centralized in the transition
 1133: modes.** In the closed and tutored operating modes Core v0 specifies for
 1134: pilots, the implementing authority constructs planning scopes; the
 1135: architecture makes that construction public, versioned, mandate-bearing,
 1136: and contestable through visibility, but in those modes it does not
 1137: distribute it. Constructing the scope means defining the frame — which
 1138: purposes, which budget share, which protected floors, which admissibility
 1139: rules — not designing or ranking projects: project creation and
 1140: prioritization remain distributed even in tutored mode, so this residual
 1141: agenda power is the power to decide what *may* be funded, never what *is*
 1142: funded. It is important not to misread our own simulation here. What that
 1143: simulation shows dominating every other quality margin is the
 1144: informational quality of the **project prioritization** — the aggregated
 1145: allocation profiles the funded share follows — and that prioritization is
 1146: distributed by design, even in tutored mode; the result is therefore an
 1147: argument *for* distributing construction, not evidence that a central
 1148: agenda governs delivery. The residual centralized power is the narrower
 1149: one: constructing the eligibility frame is itself the second face of power
 1150: (Bachrach and Baratz 1962; Schattschneider 1960; Lukes 1974) — the power
 1151: to keep something off the menu — which the architecture answers, in these
 1152: modes, by making the frame public, versioned, mandate-bearing, and
 1153: contestable rather than by distributing it. Three things scope the
 1154: limitation honestly. It is a property of the transition modes, not of the
 1155: architecture: operating modes are country-configured states, and the
 1156: designed trajectory is open, socially constructed agenda-setting. It is
 1157: narrower than the passive share: engaged citizens allocate manually,
 1158: delegate, or adopt configurable profiles, so authority weights fully
 1159: govern only the never-engaged share. And it is now measured rather than
 1160: assumed: E4 shows open construction of the weights from aggregated citizen
 1161: signals is viable and scale-robust in the model, so the constraint is no
 1162: longer whether distributed construction can work in principle but whether
 1163: an elicitation mechanism can keep dispersed signals honest, unbiased, and
 1164: representative under gaming, clientelism, and expressive-allocation
 1165: pressure — a design problem the corpus gates rather than assumes away.
 1166: The comparative baseline also belongs in this paragraph: under the current
 1167: institutional model, the entire budget follows a centrally constructed
 1168: vector that is neither published, versioned, pluggable, nor overridable by
 1169: any citizen. The transition modes reproduce that centralization visibly
 1170: and revocably; the open mode is designed to end it. This remains the
 1171: architecture's principal open problem, now with a measured prize attached
 1172: to solving it — and for that reason we treat it not as one limitation
 1173: among many but as the research program's next object: the design of open
 1174: agenda-setting, including the candidate architecture in which a
 1175: distributed agenda is constructed in parallel to the authority's own and
 1176: the tutored role narrows to admissibility review of conflicts between the
 1177: two, is the natural subject of a dedicated follow-up study and pilot.
 1178: 
 1179: **Procedural legitimacy is not democratic mandate — and the enabling norm
 1180: does not yet exist.** The platform records the external authorization for
 1181: budget migration and allocation formulas (the Allocation Mandate); it
 1182: cannot manufacture authorization the law never granted. In the continental
 1183: tradition of the reference jurisdictions, binding citizen allocation
 1184: requires an enabling instrument of sufficient rank that no current statute
 1185: supplies — the regional precedents (Peru's participatory-budgeting
 1186: statute, Brazil's city-statute framework) prove the instrument is
 1187: achievable, not that it exists — so the architecture's lawful deployments
 1188: today are consultative and tutored, in which every material allocation
 1189: decision remains imputed to the competent authority as a reasoned public
 1190: resolution; the delivery, metering, and reputational-memory results
 1191: operate unchanged under that status, and only the mature open mode
 1192: requires binding allocation. The normative debate over substituting
 1193: atomized allocation for representative appropriation (Rosanvallon 2008;
 1194: Urbinati 2014) remains open.
 1195: Under deep evaluative disagreement, the architecture's posture is
 1196: procedural in Gaus's (2011) sense: its rules aim to be justifiable from
 1197: diverse moral standpoints — which is what mandate records, motive
 1198: neutrality, and the comparative-critique discipline provide — without
 1199: presupposing a shared comprehensive doctrine. One further objection is
 1200: deliberately out of scope: the model takes the coercively raised budget as
 1201: given and improves its administration; the libertarian challenge to the
 1202: taking itself (Nozick 1974) is neither answered nor begged here.
 1203: Contribution-weighted allocation formulas, in particular, are flagged by
 1204: the architecture as plutocratic departures requiring explicit higher
 1205: authorization.
 1206: 
 1207: **Fiscal dependence is measurable, not enforceable.** The state controls
 1208: the budget spigot. The Fiscal Commitment Profile converts strangulation
 1209: from invisible to attributable — delivery latency, unexecuted valid orders,
 1210: mid-cycle share cuts all become public data — but no software compels a
 1211: sovereign to pay (Kydland and Prescott 1977; North and Weingast 1989). Credible commitment must come
 1212: from country-level law.
 1213: 
 1214: **Verification quality is assumed, then priced.** Propositions 1–4 take
 1215: detection and discovery probabilities as parameters. In thin control
 1216: markets — credence-good markets where quality is unobservable to the buyer
 1217: (Akerlof 1970; Dulleck and Kerschbamer 2006) — both collapse
 1218: simultaneously, and the only compensating margins are
 1219: financial terms and imported (remote or cross-territory) verification. The
 1220: architecture prices weak verification; it cannot conjure verifiers.
 1221: 
 1222: **Behavioral realism cuts both ways.** The simulation vindicates designing
 1223: for inattentive citizens, but it equally shows that a defaults-weak
 1224: deployment degenerates into salience-driven allocation. Off-platform
 1225: phenomena — clientelist brokerage, expressive polarization, collusion
 1226: conducted entirely outside the system — are made harder and more
 1227: discoverable, never impossible; the architecture's claims are comparative
 1228: (against opaque monopoly), not absolute.
 1229: 
 1230: **Meta-governance in open mode is deferred by design.** Rule-change
 1231: procedure, versioning, and non-surprise constraints are specified; the
 1232: constitutional mechanics — rules for making rules (Buchanan and Tullock
 1233: 1962) — of who votes on protocol changes in a mature
 1234: open-mode deployment are deliberately not. Open-mode deployment is gated on
 1235: resolving them.
 1236: 
 1237: **Adoption selects, and the thesis does not depend on it.** This paper
 1238: addresses whether the architecture can be built and how its *selection*
 1239: mechanism behaves under a symmetric, delivery-at-parity test — not whether it
 1240: delivers more value in the world (a total delivered-value effect is a separately
 1241: identified future estimand, not claimed here), and not whether any authority
 1242: wants it. The corpus supplies the
 1243: deployment layer for an authority that has decided (prospective
 1244: baselines measured from instrumentation onset, credit attribution on
 1245: verified delivery, institutional rather than personal timeout attribution
 1246: in the first cycle, and a symmetry clause barring any operator from
 1247: exempting its own projects), and names the plausible adopter archetypes —
 1248: the post-scandal challenger, the mandating higher government, the
 1249: conditioned external funder. The honest selection effect stands: the
 1250: architecture will plausibly be adopted first by relatively clean or newly
 1251: arrived sponsors, in the places that need it least.
 1252: 
 1253: **The outcome measure is a bounded, non-distributional aggregate.** The value
 1254: the model scores is a cardinal utilitarian-style sum over affected parties on a
 1255: bounded, infrastructure-like public-investment slice; it is not distributionally
 1256: weighted and says nothing about redistribution, equity, or who bears benefits and
 1257: harms. A portfolio can score well on this measure while distributing badly.
 1258: Applying the criterion across groups, or to the whole budget or the purpose of
 1259: taxation, would require a separate social-welfare and incidence specification this
 1260: paper does not provide. The model is also partial-equilibrium: strategic
 1261: reporting, endogenous proposal supply, project complementarities, tax incidence,
 1262: and general-equilibrium effects are outside it (see the
 1263: [claim-and-estimand-contract](../research/claim-and-estimand-contract.md)).
 1264: 
 1265: **Epistemically, this is one team's self-critiqued design.** The
 1266: adversarial corpus was produced by the same research effort it attacks,
 1267: with AI assistance; the earlier apparatus's status-quo baseline was
 1268: audit-parameterized (its parameters drawn item-by-item from published
 1269: audit-institution findings, with primary-source verification still in progress), while the current symmetry gate is an uncalibrated
 1270: stylized selection test — neither is calibrated to a specific PB dataset,
 1271: and the remaining parameters are plausible rather than measured; and no
 1272: pilot has been run. The three missing validations — independent expert
 1273: attack, calibration to empirical PB data, and a bounded tutored pilot
 1274: (sports-sector, one municipality) — are the research program's next
 1275: phase, in that order.
 1276: 
 1277: ## 9. Implementation pathway
 1278: 
 1279: The architecture is built for gradual, revocable adoption, and this
 1280: section is explicit about what it does and does not claim: the paper's
 1281: question — can the two-hundred-year-old allocation architecture be
 1282: re-architected with today's technology — is answered at the level of a
 1283: buildable design and a conditional selection-mechanism *direction*,
 1284: independently of whether any authority chooses to deploy. It does **not**
 1285: answer *by how much* real-world delivered value would improve: that is a
 1286: separately identified estimand left to independent review, empirical
 1287: calibration, and a bounded pilot (§8). What follows is the pathway for an
 1288: authority that chooses to deploy. A country opens
 1289: one public function (the reference pilot is municipal sports
 1290: infrastructure), migrates a small budget share under a tutored operating
 1291: mode, and retains admissibility review — with every tutored decision and
 1292: delay public by construction. The pilot's default framing is prospective:
 1293: instrumentation begins at adoption, the visibility gap is published as
 1294: the adopter's declared starting line ("measure me from here"), and
 1295: pre-adoption figures are reported separately, impersonally, and as
 1296: context — the configuration under which exposing instruments have
 1297: historically been adopted. Functional maturity metrics (participation
 1298: mix, default-flow share, fiscalization independence rates, incumbent-
 1299: resistance indicators, fiscal reliability) determine whether the deployment
 1300: earns wider scope, and their trajectories, not rhetoric, answer whether
 1301: distribution outperforms the local baseline. The exit condition is honest
 1302: in both directions: a pilot whose indicators stagnate under incumbent
 1303: throttling documents that fact publicly, which is itself information the
 1304: current system never yields.
 1305: 
 1306: The transition between regimes is itself measured. The companion
 1307: experiments (Offermann 2026b) quantify the semi-open regime of the
 1308: operating-regime ladder (docs/110) — a bounded mandated envelope running on
 1309: protocol autopilot beside the authority's traditional budget — as a fiscal
 1310: blend: above a portfolio-granularity floor of roughly ten percent, blended
 1311: verified value rises monotonically and near-linearly with the envelope
 1312: share within that apparatus, from break-even near eight to ten percent
 1313: upward — an earlier-apparatus contrast now subject to the retired-multiplier
 1314: caveat (Section 6), not a calibrated endpoint. The transition from the status
 1315: quo toward the open regime is a dial, not a leap: adoption can proceed in
 1316: increments.
 1317: 
 1318: The same experiments measured a variable this corpus had left unregulated:
 1319: *when* the authority releases budget into the allocation machinery. The
 1320: resulting deployment rule: meter release against a work-in-progress ceiling
 1321: calibrated to the delivery-and-verification pipeline's throughput and cycle
 1322: time — never against the calendar. Calendar release freezes months of
 1323: budget in escrow and saturates verification; and when verification capacity
 1324: is scarce, no release policy compensates — verification capacity is the
 1325: pipeline's ceiling before it is the anti-fraud instrument. The rule is
 1326: conditional on a carryforward instrument (the semi-open envelope is
 1327: precisely such a vehicle); under strict budget annuality it degenerates to
 1328: within-year metering.
 1329: 
 1330: Finally, the technological premise that lowers participation costs on the
 1331: citizen side (the AI tutor) applies symmetrically to the control side.
 1332: Machine verification of protocolizable evidence classes multiplies
 1333: fiscalization capacity, with humans as the permanent second instance —
 1334: sampled re-verification with a published floor, seeded known-answer
 1335: controls as the calibration and drift-detection instrument, auditing the
 1336: verifier rather than competing with it — so that the machine's error rate
 1337: remains measured and the human control profession remains funded from the
 1338: control budget it relieves. Measured on a five-family panel of real models
 1339: (Offermann 2026b), frontier models converge on good specificity and fraud
 1340: detection on document-legible evidence while small local models are weaker,
 1341: and evidence contracts that include objective comparison references (market
 1342: benchmarks, duration bands, thresholds) let a strict verifier judge rather
 1343: than guess. The machine layer reaches only document-legible, delivery-phase
 1344: fraud — physical quality-below-spec and pre-contract theft remain fully
 1345: human, so provenance attestation is tamper-evidence at capture, not
 1346: court-grade proof, and evidentiary admissibility still needs custody, contradiction,
 1347: and expert testimony. Contraposed citizen evidence — independent producers
 1348: with interests opposed to the executor, whose anticipated existence deters
 1349: diversion — keeps the watching distributed even as routine
 1350: document-verification labor shrinks; but its strength equals the
 1351: *independence* of the contributor layer, and a colluding ring that captures
 1352: or silences it erases the effect. Cross-layer collusion is in fact the one
 1353: adversary that bypasses the per-milestone deterrence and moves leakage by an
 1354: order of magnitude (while the delivered-value advantage survives), so
 1355: collusion resistance — verified beneficial ownership, contributor
 1356: Sybil-resistance, and decentralization of the assigner and the audit-budget
 1357: floor — is a first-class requirement ([docs/113](../docs/113_VERIFICATION_PACKAGE_AND_A043_RESOLUTION.md)), not a residual caution.
 1358: 
 1359: ## 10. Conclusion
 1360: 
 1361: For the bounded public-investment allocation problem studied here, a
 1362: relevant criterion is not how faithfully an institution executes a plan
 1363: but how much delivered, verified value it produces per unit of public
 1364: resource (Musgrave 1959; Okun 1975) — one criterion alongside the
 1365: distributional and rights constraints this model does not represent. This
 1366: paper's contribution is an architecture that makes that criterion
 1367: operational — and a disciplined account of exactly how far its evidence
 1368: reaches. The
 1369: architecture's spine is two separable questions anyone can ask. First:
 1370: take the same projects, designed identically, and change only who
 1371: executes and how they are watched — does the visibly audited regime with
 1372: reputational consequences deliver more than the one without them? Second:
 1373: hold the control layer fixed and change only which projects get funded,
 1374: centrally planned or socially prioritized? In the exploratory simulation
 1375: apparatus the answer to both is yes — a verified-delivery gain and a
 1376: selection gain that interact rather than merely add — but those
 1377: magnitudes are model-internal factorial contrasts, not calibrated
 1378: effects, and we do not build the paper on them. The claim the paper
 1379: actually stands on is narrower and was tested harder: a pre-registered,
 1380: symmetric, selection-only gate finds the distributed-minus-central
 1381: advantage positive in every cell but small (a pre-registered pooled median
 1382: Δ = 0.025 of a full-information benchmark, below its pre-set 0.05
 1383: research-program rebuild gate), so we retire the compound multiplier an
 1384: earlier version reported and rest on the architecture and the *direction*
 1385: of the mechanism. One model-internal result is worth carrying because it is
 1386: about the delivery layer, not the multiplier: in the model, at E7's
 1387: audit-informed (but not yet fully source-verified) detection intensity,
 1388: detection without persistent consequences deters no diversion; what moves delivered value is the
 1389: instrument the modelled status quo lacks — consequences that persist. Whether
 1390: that holds in a real institution is a hypothesis for a pilot, not a result
 1391: here; but the model is unambiguous that accountability without memory is
 1392: bookkeeping.
 1393: 
 1394: The deeper point is Friedman's: a central administration spends other
 1395: people's money on other people, the spending category with the least care
 1396: for both cost and value (Friedman and Friedman 1980). This architecture
 1397: does not answer that problem with exhortation; it re-plumbs the bucket.
 1398: Planning remains — as the guiding thread that sets scopes, floors, and
 1399: mandates — but the engine of value is the conversion layer: measurable
 1400: promises, conditional release, independent verification, consequences that
 1401: compound into reputation, and a meter on every leak. The question this
 1402: paper answers is therefore not whether states should be bigger or smaller,
 1403: but whether the layers of state activity that fail through information and
 1404: incentive monopoly can be re-architected to fail less — and to show their
 1405: failures when they do. For one such layer we have specified a complete
 1406: architecture, proved the incentive conditions its mechanisms depend on,
 1407: measured selection, aggregation, and delivery in simulation against a
 1408: baseline the incumbent system's own auditors supplied, and subjected
 1409: the whole to five rounds of documented adversarial review with an
 1410: explicit integrate-or-bound discipline. The result is deliberately modest
 1411: in its claims and unusually explicit about their edges: allocation quality
 1412: rides on the informational quality of whatever constructs the weight
 1413: vector, whose open construction is measured viable but whose honest
 1414: elicitation remains the open problem; delivered value rides on
 1415: verification whose market conditions must be priced; legitimacy rides on
 1416: mandates the platform can record but not create. What distinguishes the
 1417: proposal is that these edges are specified, monitored, and attached to
 1418: named objects — which is, we argue, what it looks like when institutional
 1419: design is treated as an engineering discipline rather than an ideological
 1420: one.
 1421: 
 1422: ## Appendix: E4 calibration targets
 1423: 
 1424: The E4-v4/v5 magnitudes are model-internal; the table names, for each parameter, the
 1425: real dataset that *could* inform it — making the boundary between model-internal and
 1426: empirically-anchored a visible line rather than a caveat buried in prose (details in
 1427: `research/e4-calibration-targets.md`). The central %-benchmark is an *output* the
 1428: model computes, but mapping it to observed realized-to-appraised ratios is **not a
 1429: direct overlay**: the two are different constructs (§6), so it is a **candidate
 1430: validation target requiring an explicit construct bridge**, not a one-step
 1431: calibration.
 1432: 
 1433: | Model quantity | Model value | Real-world proxy | Candidate dataset(s) | Status |
 1434: |---|---|---|---|---|
 1435: | central %-benchmark | 46–68% | realized ÷ appraised value | World Bank IEG ratings; Flyvbjerg megaproject DB | candidate target; needs an explicit construct mapping |
 1436: | η (harm-blindness) | 0–0.5 | passive vs active waste share | Bandiera-Prat-Valletti 2009 (83% passive, setting-specific: Italian standardized-goods procurement) | anchored-direction |
 1437: | β (voice inequality) | 0.2–0.5 | PB participation bias | NYC / Paris / Porto Alegre; Decidim / Consul | calibratable |
 1438: | q, m (detection) | q ≈ 0.5–1%, m in hundreds | complaint / whistleblowing rates | FTC Consumer Sentinel; NYC 311; Dyck et al. 2010 | calibratable |
 1439: | λ threshold | central ≈ 0.10 | procurement rents / bribe depth | Olken 2007; WB Enterprise Surveys | calibratable |
 1440: | penalty f | equal both sides | legal sanction scale | held equal (conservative) | scope choice |
