 165: ## Regrounding the macro stage + unifying the two frictions
 166: 
 167: **Law of 1/n (structural, not perceptual).** The macro coefficient η need not be assumed
 168: as *myopia*. Under **Weingast, Shepsle & Johnsen (1981, JPE 89:642–664)** a sector's
 169: benefits are locally concentrated while its costs are shared across the A areas of the
 170: fiscal commons, so each area internalizes only 1/A of the cost: net-harm is
 171: **externalized, not merely unperceived.** This is a strict upgrade of η — it derives
 172: harm-blindness from the structure of shared financing rather than positing it. Pair with
 173: **Primo & Snyder (2008, JOP 70:477–486)**: the 1/n distortion *weakens as n grows*,
 174: making η **regime-dependent** — exactly the shape of our η-frontier rather than a single
 175: point. The perceptual micro-story remains available as a complement: **Buchanan & Wagner
 176: (1977)** fiscal illusion (voters under-perceive the deferred/diffuse cost) and
 177: **Niskanen (1971)** budget-maximizing bureaus that over-weight visible S⁺.
 178: 
 179: **Common-Cause Proposition.** η and β are **two faces of one Olson asymmetry**, not
 180: independent frictions. The diffuse harmed (i) fail to organize, so the central perceives
 181: value through *organized* proxies and under-counts their harm → η low; and (ii) fail to
 182: self-select into voice, so they are missing from the participating sample → β high. The
 183: parity race β\* = 1 − η is thus a contest between two *manifestations of the same
 184: failure*. The asymmetry is that the central's blindness is **structural and
 185: irreparable** (money and organization, not headcount, set its ledger), whereas the
 186: distributed's β is **bounded and repairable** by the default-routing / delegation layer —
 187: a Hirschman (1970) voice-substitute for those who would otherwise stay silent. Grounding:
 188: Olson 1965, Hirschman 1970, Verba-Schlozman-Brady 1995; β is in part the shadow of
 189: **Hurwicz** (a decentralized, message-bounded mechanism cannot be simultaneously
 190: informationally efficient and incentive-compatible).
 191: 
 192: ---
 193: 
 194: ## Impossibilities we own (claim the right theorem, not the wrong one)
 195: 
 196: The architecture should *cite the impossibility it lives inside* rather than be ambushed
 197: by it:
 198: - **Green & Laffont (1979):** no dominant-strategy mechanism is efficient, budget-balanced
 199:   and individually rational at once — so we do **not** claim VCG-style efficiency; the
 200:   contribution is *comparative* value-preservation under realistic frictions.
 201: - **Gibbard–Satterthwaite:** any non-dictatorial rule is manipulable — so we claim
 202:   **capture-resistance** (backbone Prop 2–3: the cost/detection floor), **not**
 203:   strategy-proofness.
 204: - **Hurwicz:** the informational-efficiency / incentive-compatibility tension **is** the
 205:   voice-bias β — named, bounded, and partly repairable, not wished away.
 206: - **Arrow (1951)** is **escaped**, not violated: aggregation is a **cardinal Samuelson
 207:   sum**, not an ordinal social-welfare function, so the independence/transitivity
 208:   impossibility does not bind (flag the normative cost with the Sen 1979 caveat on
 209:   interpersonal cardinal comparison).
 210: - **Myerson–Satterthwaite:** efficient bilateral trade under private values is impossible
 211:   — bounds what any allocation stage, ours included, can achieve; another reason the claim
 212:   is comparative.
 213: 
 214: ---
 215: 
 216: ## Scope conditions (state them; they make the gap a *lower bound*)
 217: - **Exogenous agenda.** The choice set / project agenda is taken as given and identical
 218:   across arms. This is *generous to the central* (it ignores the distributed arm's
 219:   agenda-setting advantage), so the measured gap is a **lower bound** on the full-system
 220:   difference.
 221: - **Additive separability.** Value aggregates additively across projects (Samuelson); no
 222:   cross-project complementarities beyond those declared in composite programs. Flagged,
 223:   not assumed away.
 224: - **Symmetric frictions.** Both arms carry a first-order friction (central η, distributed
 225:   β) and the capture model is symmetric (backbone Prop 2) — the frontier is a *fair*
 226:   comparison, not a tilted one.
 227: 
 228: ## What this changes for the paper
 229: Finding 4/5 should carry a compact **"Analytical propositions"** box stating A
 230: (sign-flip / asymmetry-not-variance), B (compound parity β\*_pipe = 1 − η + δ, O-ring

