===== ANALYTIC BACKBONE =====
    1: # E4 — Analytical Backbone: three closed forms the simulations obey
    2: 
    3: > **🛑 MAGNITUDES RETIRED (2026-07-10, LATEST — controlling).** Every multiplier in this note (and the
    4: > "~99% of oracle at <1% net-negative" / "pre-registered 7/7" framing in the banner below) is **retired**.
    5: > The independent audit (`audits/2026-07-10/`) and the pre-registered **symmetry gate (NO-GO)** showed the
    6: > distributed selection advantage is real but small (pre-registered pooled median ~0.025 of a full-information benchmark (post-hoc ratio-of-sums 0.026), below
    7: > its 0.05 research-program rebuild gate). Controlling doc: `research/claim-and-estimand-contract.md`. This note is kept
    8: > as analytical/mechanism history; its closed forms illustrate the *direction*, not calibrated sizes.
    9: >
   10: > ---
   11: >
   12: > **CORRECTION / SUPERSEDED AS PRIMARY MECHANISM (2026-07-10).** The parity law **β\* = 1 − η**
   13: > (Proposition 1) models the distributed advantage as the central being **blind to harm**. Value
   14: > model v2 (`e4e5-value-model-v2.md`, `e5-sp-model.mjs`, pre-registered 7/7) showed — and confirmed
   15: > on held-out seeds — that **harm-blindness is nearly inert when net-harm is rare** (a harm-blind
   16: > central still delivers ~99% of oracle at <1% net-negative projects, which the author establishes is
   17: > the real world). The **primary** mechanism is instead **agenda-capture**: the central maximizes
   18: > political credit-claiming **P** (Mayhew 1974 / Arnold 1990 / Gilens-Page 2014), misaligned with
   19: > social value **S** at corr(S,P) < 1. `e5-sp-model.mjs` is the corrected E4 — it **nests** this
   20: > backbone (its `w=1` reproduces the harm-blind central) and adds the agenda-capture central (`w=0`).
   21: > **This backbone remains valid as the RARE DIVISIVE / net-harmful SPECIAL CASE** (where Sp≈Sm and
   22: > harm actually bites), not the headline. Props 2–3 (capture threshold, detection floor) and the
   23: > invariances are unaffected. Read this note as "the special-case algebra"; read v2 for the modal
   24: > mechanism.
   25: 
   26: ## Status
   27: The constructive-review round (see `e4-constructive-review-synthesis.md`) found that
   28: the entire E4 line (v4 frontier + v5 capture) is governed by three closed-form
   29: results that the simulations merely instantiate. Making them explicit converts the
   30: contribution from "a seeded simulation whose magnitudes are model-internal" into
   31: "an analytical result confirmed by simulation, with the simulation quantifying the
   32: degradation the algebra cannot." Verified in `e4-analytical-backbone.mjs`
   33: (results: `e4-analytical-backbone-results.txt`). The simulation is demoted to
   34: illustration + degradation-quantification.
   35: 
   36: **Symbol note.** This note and the simulation code write the central's harm-perception
   37: coefficient as **γ** (`gamma`). The *paper* renames it **η** to avoid a collision with
   38: the posted-guarantee γ of Propositions 1–3 (the delivery/incentive model). Read γ here
   39: as η in the paper; the parity law is β* = 1 − γ ≡ β* = 1 − η.
   40: 
   41: ## Proposition 1 — the parity law β\* = 1 − γ (with a bias–variance reading)
   42: 
   43: **Setup.** For a project, let `S⁺` = sum of the positive true valuations and `S⁻` =
   44: sum of the absolute values of the negative valuations. Its true social value is
   45: `T = S⁺ − S⁻` (Samuelson aggregate; can be negative = net harm). Each institution
   46: ranks projects by a **harm-discounted estimate**
   47: 
   48: > **T̂ = S⁺ − θ · S⁻**  (+ second-order noise),  with harm-coefficient **θ**.
   49: 
   50: - **Central** perceives benefit fully but keeps only γ of perceived harm ⇒ **θ_C = γ**.
   51: - **Distributed** reads true valuations, but the harmed participate only at rate
   52:   (1 − β); the global participation rate p multiplies every score equally and so
   53:   **cancels from the ranking** ⇒ **θ_D = 1 − β**.
   54: 
   55: **Proposition 1.** The true harm-weight is 1. The institution whose θ is closer to 1
   56: ranks projects closer to the truth and delivers more true value. Since
   57: |1 − θ_C| = 1 − γ and |1 − θ_D| = β,
   58: 
   59: > **distributed dominates ⇔ β < 1 − γ**,  with the **parity locus β\* = 1 − γ**
   60: > (the anti-diagonal of the γ×β frontier).
   61: 
   62: **Verification.** The noise-free, sample-free analytical estimators give advantage
   63: **exactly 1.00 on every anti-diagonal cell** (γ+β=1): (0,1), (.25,.75), (.5,.5),
   64: (.75,.25), (1,0) → 1.00. The full simulation reproduces this to within seed noise,
   65: with one informative deviation:
   66: 
   67: **Bias–variance reading (predicts the one "anomaly").** Decompose each estimator's
   68: error into bias and variance:
   69: - **Bias:** central overstates harm-laden projects by (1−γ)·S⁻; distributed by β·S⁻.
   70:   The mean advantage is driven by the bias gap — this is Proposition 1.
   71: - **Variance:** central carries irreducible **proxy noise** (∝ noise²·n_interested);
   72:   distributed carries **sampling variance** (∝ p(1−p)·Σv²) but **zero revelation
   73:   noise** — the funder knows her own value.
   74: 
   75: On the parity line the bias cancels, so the **lower-variance** estimator wins. Because
   76: the central's proxy noise generically exceeds the distributed's (which is zero on
   77: revelation), the *measured* parity line sits slightly on the distributed's side —
   78: exactly the simulation's **(γ=1, β=0) → 0.89** cell, which a reader would otherwise
   79: call an anomaly. This is the textbook **biased-census vs unbiased-subsample** tradeoff:
   80: subsampling beats bias exactly when the harm-discount (1−γ) exceeds the participation
   81: bias β.
   82: 
   83: ## Proposition 2 — the capture threshold ρ(C)
   84: 
   85: From the Becker capture condition `rent > acquisition + P(detect)·penalty` with
   86: rent = λ·C (λ = rent as a fraction of project cost C):
   87: 
   88: > **λ\*_central = (k_c + p_c·F) / C**   (fixed acquisition k_c, low detection p_c)
   89: > **λ\*_distributed = k_d + p_d·F / C**  (acquisition scales with C; viral detection p_d≈1)
   90: > **resistance ratio ρ(C) = (k_d·C + p_d·F) / (k_c + p_c·F)**
   91: 
   92: **Verification** (k_c=0.3, p_c=0.1, k_d=0.3, p_d≈0.97, F=3, matching e4-v5):
   93: λ\*_central ≈ 0.06–0.20 (matches the sim's net-harmful onset ≈0.10); λ\*_distributed
   94: ≈ 0.59–1.27; **ρ = 6.3× (C=3) → 7.6× (C=5.5) → 9.8× (C=10)** — rising in project cost.
   95: 
   96: **The structural content the prose only gestured at:** the central threshold **→ 0**
   97: as its detection/fixed cost shrinks relative to C (a cheap-to-capture institution has
   98: essentially no floor), whereas the distributed threshold has an **irreducible floor
   99: k_d** — the equal-wallet acquisition scaling — that **no rent can erode**, because
  100: money cannot buy equal wallets, only persuade their holders. The ~10× is ρ evaluated
  101: at representative cost, not a simulation artifact.
  102: 
  103: ## Proposition 3 — the detection-floor theorem
  104: 
  105: Under snowball detection (a captured project is exposed if at least one of m affected
  106: citizens reports, each independently with probability q):
  107: 
  108: > **P(detection) = 1 − (1 − q)^m ⇒ m·q = −ln(1 − P).**
  109: 
  110: **Proposition 3.** Distributed detection exceeds a fixed central rate p_c iff the
  111: **expected reporter count** satisfies **m·q > −ln(1 − p_c)**; a general detection level
  112: p requires **m·q ≥ −ln(1 − p)**. Only the **product** m·q matters — the floor is
  113: invariant to how reporters split between few-but-motivated (high q) and
  114: many-but-informed (high m).
  115: 
  116: **Verification** (reproduces the floor table to the decimal): beat the central
  117: (p_c=0.10) → m·q ≈ **0.11**; p=0.50 → 0.69; strong p=0.90 → **2.30**; near-viral
  118: p=0.99 → **4.61**. The floor is logarithmically cheap: beating the status quo needs an
  119: expected **~0.1 reporters** per captured project. This makes the burden-of-proof
  120: inversion **rigorous, not rhetorical**: to defeat the distributed arm a skeptic must
  121: assert m·q < 0.1 — near-total civic apathy among people cheated of a benefit they were
  122: owed.
  123: 
  124: ## Invariance propositions (pre-empt the "arbitrary magnitudes" attack)
  125: - **Scale-invariance.** The advantage is a ratio of delivered true values; under
  126:   N_i → c·N_i (c>0) every S⁺, S⁻ and estimator scales by c, rankings are unchanged ⇒
  127:   the frontier's shape and the parity line are invariant to the units of value. The
  128:   "magnitudes are arbitrary" objection cannot touch the frontier's structure.
  129: - **Turnout-invariance.** The distributed participation rate p is a global multiplier
  130:   on all scores ⇒ it does not change the ranking, only the zero-gate position. The
  131:   result depends on the **bias** β in who participates, **not** on how many do.
  132: - **Shape-invariance (CLT).** T_j = Σ_i N_i sums over tens–hundreds of interested
  133:   citizens; by the CLT its distribution is ≈ normal regardless of the per-citizen
  134:   valuation shape, and only S⁺, S⁻ (first moments of the positive/negative parts)
  135:   enter the estimators ⇒ the Gaussian draw is a convenience, not a load-bearing
  136:   assumption.
  137: 
  138: ## What this changes
  139: The paper should carry a short **"Analytical results"** statement of Propositions 1–3
  140: and the three invariances, with the simulations explicitly demoted to (a) confirming
  141: the closed forms and (b) quantifying the delivered-value degradation as parameters
  142: move off the clean cases. Every downstream claim — the frontier, the capture
  143: threshold, the abstract — then inherits the credibility of a proven law rather than a
  144: fitted table.

