audits\2026-07-10-round2\high-value-improvements.md:25:2. **The central appraisal budget is approximately, not exactly, matched.** The code uses `K × round(expReports/K)` with a one-observation-per-project floor (`scripts/simulation/e5-sp-symmetry-gate.mjs:70-78`), whereas the design describes the expected distributed report total as the central budget (`audits/2026-07-10/symmetry-gate-preregistration.md:29-31`). The numerical effect is **unverified**; exact integer apportionment should remove the discrepancy in the new engine.
audits\2026-07-10-round2\high-value-improvements.md:185:**Why it matters:** With no pilot and preliminary prior art (`drafts/paper.md:349-384,1240-1250`), the present manuscript is a poor fit for venues demanding the strongest theoretical or empirical contribution. After recommendations 1, 7, and 10, **Government Information Quarterly** is the best initial fit because its official scope includes significant theoretical/practical contributions at the government–technology–public intersection, transparent/accountable government, and participatory decision-making ([official scope](https://www.sciencedirect.com/journal/government-information-quarterly)). **Policy & Internet** is a plausible alternative if the paper emphasizes how digital infrastructure reshapes participation, power, and governance ([official scope](https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/page/journal/19442866/homepage/productinformation.html)). A later causal pilot could credibly aim at **JPART**, whose stated standard is the highest-quality theoretical and empirical public-administration work ([official journal page](https://academic.oup.com/jpart)).
audits\2026-07-10-round2\high-value-improvements.md:203:### 15. Add automated bilingual parity and archive separation
audits\2026-07-10-round3\honesty-overclaiming.md:19:- **What is wrong:** The limitations section correctly says the paper addresses how a stylized *selection* mechanism behaves under delivery parity, “not whether it delivers more value in the world,” and reserves total delivered value for a separately identified future estimand (`drafts/paper.md:1154-1158`). Thirty lines later, the implementation section says the research question—whether the allocation architecture “can be improved with today's technology, and by how much”—“is answered” (`drafts/paper.md:1184-1188`). It supplies no in-model qualifier and does not narrow “by how much” to the small conditional selection contrast.
audits\2026-07-10-round2\multidimensional-evaluation.md:7:The Path-B correction is substantively real: the controlling contract limits the surviving quantitative claim to a small, conditional selection effect, and the deterministic gate reproduces the reported NO-GO. The current manuscript, however, has not completed that pivot: its abstract and conclusion still use retired or superseded apparatus outputs as headline evidence, including +43% delivery and +53–54% selection, although the contract says a delivery-inclusive effect is future work and “not claimed here.” Several fresh defects weaken rigor further: earlier experiments are still called pre-registered contrary to the controlling contract, the E4 parity discussion reverses the meaning of a 0.89 distributed/central ratio, and the prominent ~10× capture claim is largely generated by stipulated detection and acquisition-cost asymmetries. This is a potentially useful and unusually specified architecture paper, but the current v1.13 draft remains a **major-revisions working paper**, not yet a clean architecture-plus-mechanism contribution.
audits\2026-07-10-round2\multidimensional-evaluation.md:33:7. **Novelty is plausible but unverified.** The related-work section usefully distinguishes the proposal from polycentric governance, participatory budgeting, fiscal federalism, liquid democracy, and mechanism design (`drafts/paper.md:260-343`). But its own novelty claim is expressly “pending a systematic prior-art review” (`drafts/paper.md:345-377`), and the literature map calls itself initial and leaves “find papers that support, contradict, or partially anticipate each component” as a research task (`research/literature-map.md:1-4,33-39`). The defensible novelty claim is therefore integration and object-level specification; field-level priority is **unverified**.
audits\2026-07-10-round2\multidimensional-evaluation.md:75:The project addresses a consequential problem and names plausible users: municipalities or authorities testing a bounded tutored allocation layer, with explicit maturity metrics and exit conditions (`drafts/paper.md:1231-1254`). Its object model and transition ladder could organize pilots and interdisciplinary debate even without a large effect. Impact is capped because binding citizen allocation lacks an enabling norm, verification supply is assumed, mature meta-governance is deferred, and adoption likely selects relatively clean sponsors (`drafts/paper.md:1149-1218`); no pilot has run (`drafts/paper.md:1220-1229`). The small, uncalibrated selection sign supports a research agenda, not a current policy performance claim.
audits\2026-07-10-round2\multidimensional-evaluation.md:107:**Would I recommend publishing the working paper now, as an honest architecture+mechanism contribution? No.** First remove or demote the old apparatus magnitudes from the abstract and conclusion, reconcile all preregistration labels with the contract, correct the E4 ratio/parity errors, and import the contract's welfare/scope limits; after those bounded revisions, an honest architecture-plus-qualitative-mechanism working paper would be defensible.
